Rule 12b-2 of the Act ).&#160; Yes&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font face="Wingdings">o</font>&#160;&#160; No&nbsp;&nbsp;<font face="Wingdings">&#253;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
aggregate market value of the common shares (the only common equity of the
registrant) held by non-affiliates of the registrant based on the price at
which the common shares were last sold as of June 30, 2004, the last business
day of the registrant&#146;s most recently completed second fiscal quarter, was
$45,080,293.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
number of the registrant&#146;s common shares outstanding as of March 28, 2005: <b><font style="font-weight:bold;">10,118,583.</font></b></font></p>

<div style="border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 9.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;">

<p style="border:none;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;padding:0in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

</div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><a name="PartI"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">PART I</font></b></a></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item1Business"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 1 -
BUSINESS</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">General</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc. (&#147;AirNet&#148;) is a specialty air carrier for
time-sensitive deliveries, operating between most U.S. cities each working
day.&#160; AirNet is the leading transporter
of cancelled checks and related information for the U.S. banking industry.&#160; AirNet also provides specialized,
high-priority delivery services to customers, primarily those involved in the
medical, critical parts and entertainment industries.&#160; AirNet also provides passenger charter
services through its wholly-owned subsidiary, Jetride, Inc.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operates a fleet of 115 aircraft (including 33 Learjets and 15
Cessna Caravan turboprops) that depart from over 120 cities and complete more
than 480 flights per night, primarily Monday through Thursday.&#160;&#160; In addition, Jetride, Inc. operates 13
Learjets and 2 Challengers that offer private passenger charter services.&#160; To supplement its air transportation network,
AirNet uses commercial airlines during daytime and weekend hours when its
aircraft are operating under a limited flight schedule.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition to regularly scheduled delivery services, AirNet offers
on-demand cargo charter delivery services.&#160;
AirNet provides ground pick-up and delivery services throughout the
nation seven days per week, using a combination of company personnel and a
network of vendors and independent contractors.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s integrated air and ground network provides dependable,
time-critical delivery services to its customers.&#160; Later pick-up and earlier delivery times than
those offered by other national carriers is one of the primary differentiating
characteristics of AirNet&#146;s time-critical delivery network.&#160; AirNet&#146;s flight schedule is designed to
provide delivery times between midnight and 8:00 a.m., providing earlier
delivery times than those generally available through other national
carriers.&#160; AirNet uses a number of
proprietary customer service and management information systems to track, sort,
dispatch and control the flow of packages throughout AirNet&#146;s delivery
system.&#160; AirNet provides customer service
24 hours per day, seven days a week to handle any inquiries, discrepancies or
supply requests, as well as to provide proof of delivery documentation, all of
which are value-added features of AirNet&#146;s service.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc. was incorporated as a C-corporation under the laws
of the State of Ohio on February&nbsp;15, 1996.&#160;
AirNet&#146;s principal executive offices are located at
3939&nbsp;International Gateway, Columbus, Ohio 43219, and can be reached at
(614) 237-9777.&#160; AirNet&#146;s Internet web
site address is </font>www.airnet.com
(this uniform resource locator (URL) is an inactive textual reference only and
is not intended to incorporate AirNet&#146;s web site into this Annual Report on
Form 10-K).</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet makes available free of charge, on or through its Internet web
site, its annual report on Form 10-K, quarterly reports on Form 10-Q, current
reports on Form 8-K, and amendments to those reports filed or furnished
pursuant to Section 13(a) or 15(d) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as
amended (the &#147;Exchange Act&#148;), as soon as reasonably practicable after AirNet
electronically files such material with, or furnishes it to, the Securities and
Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As further described in &#147;Note 3 &#150; Segment Reporting&#148; of the Notes to
Consolidated Financial Statements included in &#147;Item 8 &#150; Financial Statements
and Supplementary Data&#148; of this Annual Report on Form 10-K, AirNet operates two
distinct reportable segments, Delivery Services and Passenger Charter
Services.&#160; AirNet&#146;s Delivery Services
segment provides delivery service of time-critical shipments for Bank customers
and other Express customers.&#160; AirNet&#146;s
Passenger Charter Services segment provides passenger charter service.&#160; Financial information for AirNet&#146;s reportable
segments is provided in &#147;Note 3 &#150; Segment Reporting&#148; of the Notes to
Consolidated Financial Statements and is incorporated herein by reference.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Delivery Services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Bank services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 31.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Bank services, primarily consisting of cancelled check delivery,
generated approximately 61%, 69% and 72% of AirNet&#146;s revenues for the fiscal
years ended December 31, 2004, 2003 and 2002, respectively.&#160; AirNet&#146;s time-critical cancelled check
delivery service allows its banking customers to reduce their float costs and
related processing fees.&#160; AirNet also
transports other items, such as proof of deposit transactions and interoffice
mail, for many of the same bank customers.&#160;
AirNet has historically priced its Bank services based on the tier of
service, and by the pound, on a customer-by-customer basis.&#160; The U.S. banking industry, including
commercial banks and third party processors, represents AirNet&#146;s largest
category of customers. AirNet&#146;s bank customers represent over 100 of the nation&#146;s
largest bank holding companies.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 31.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Express services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 31.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Express services, which focus on customers with time-critical delivery
needs, generated approximately 28%, 25% and 24% of AirNet&#146;s revenues for the
fiscal years ended December 31, 2004, 2003 and 2002, respectively.&#160; Express</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='3',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">services are primarily targeted at customers involved in the medical,
critical parts and entertainment industries.&#160;
In the medical industry, Express services are offered to customers shipping
packages that require specialized handling, the transportation of which is
often highly regulated by various governmental authorities.&#160; Targeted markets within the medical industry
include producers and recipients of radioactive pharmaceuticals, diagnostic
specimens, blood, umbilical cord blood, human tissue and organs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 31.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Express services are also marketed to customers whose shipment needs
are highly time sensitive or time definite, including critical parts suppliers
and customers involved in the media and entertainment industries.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 31.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For those customers requiring time-critical delivery options not
available on AirNet&#146;s regularly scheduled routes, on-demand cargo charter
services are available 24 hours per day, seven days a week.&#160; On-demand charters may be scheduled in
advance or on an as-needed basis.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 31.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Passenger Charter Services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Jetride, Inc., a wholly-owned subsidiary of AirNet which generated
approximately 11%, 5% and 3% of AirNet&#146;s revenues for the fiscal years ended
December 31, 2004, 2003 and 2002, respectively, provides private passenger
charter services that offer customers a safe, fast, and convenient way to
travel.&#160; Jetride&#146;s private passenger
charter service is available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week primarily within the
continental United States and neighboring countries.&#160; Jetride provides charter services arranged
through third-party charter brokers and, to a lesser extent, to retail
customers.&#160; Jetride operates its 13
passenger Learjets and 2 passenger Challengers from ten locations across the
country.&#160; Jetride&#146;s fleet consists of
nine owned aircraft and six aircraft that are managed for other owners.&#160; Jetride&#146;s fleet of Learjets and Challengers
are configured to comfortably carry eight to twelve passengers.&#160; All passenger charter pilots are Airline
Transport Pilot rated &#150; the highest Federal Aviation Administration (&#147;FAA&#148;)
rating possible.&#160; Jetride, </font>Inc. is certified by the Wyvern Network of
Charter Operators and holds an Aviation Research Group/US Platinum rating, the
highest rating in the industry.&#160; Further
expansion of the Jetride fleet in 2005 is projected to be through managed
aircraft.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Aviation Services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operates a fixed base operation from AirNet&#146;s Columbus, Ohio
facility, offering retail aviation fuel sales and related ground support
services.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Business Strategy</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet continues to transition and diversify by pursuing growth
opportunities for its Express and Passenger Charter services.&#160; AirNet is focusing on expanding its Express
services to customers in time-critical markets and time-definite delivery
markets, such as medical, radioactive pharmaceutical and on-demand cargo
charters.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet believes that demand for private passenger charter services will
continue to grow as commercial airlines continue to tighten schedules and
require long boarding times due to security concerns.&#160; To capitalize on the increased demand, Jetride
has increased the number of owned and managed aircraft.&#160; In the fourth quarter of 2004, Jetride
increased its managed aircraft fleet by adding two large cabin Challenger jet
aircraft to its charter offering.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet believes that its Bank services revenue will decline in future
periods as a result of the continuing evolution of electronic alternatives to
the physical movement of cancelled checks.&#160;&#160; The Check 21 Act, which became effective in
October 2004, requires that all financial
institutions accept either the physical cancelled check, or an image
replacement document in lieu of a physical cancelled check.&#160; AirNet believes that this will accelerate the
transition in the banking industry to the electronic clearing of cancelled
checks.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet continues to evaluate its operational structure and associated
costs to more closely align them with the expected volume and revenue
changes.&#160; Given the high fixed cost
nature of AirNet&#146;s national airline network, it will be difficult to reduce
costs in proportion to decreases in bank revenues.&#160; AirNet continues to evaluate its pricing for
Bank customers and may introduce pricing that contains additional fixed fees
that would be impacted to a lesser degree by decreasing volume.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The continuing diversification of AirNet&#146;s business will likely require
significant changes in its air transportation network, including a reduction in
its current route schedule, additional investment in sales and marketing during
the transition, and investment in additional service capabilities and
technologies to serve a more diverse customer group.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Fast Forward Solutions</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Fast Forward Solutions, LLC, a wholly-owned subsidiary
of AirNet, was formed to explore growth opportunities associated with existing
and emerging image replacement platforms and technologies. </font>Fast Forward Solutions and NetDeposit, Inc.
signed a term sheet in 2003 regarding their intent to finalize an agreement
related to the joint development and marketing of image replacement products
and services.&#160; Fast Forward Solutions is
no longer actively pursuing an agreement with NetDeposit, Inc.&#160; Fast Forward Solutions will continue to
explore opportunities in the image replacement market as they</p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">4</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='4',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">arise,
focusing on image replacement solutions that require both technology and the
physical movement of image replacement documents.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Operations</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Air operations</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s air operations are headquartered in Columbus, Ohio.&#160; AirNet and Jetride utilize an extensive
screening process to evaluate potential pilots prior to hiring.&#160; New pilots must meet stringent company
qualifications, as well as mandated FAA requirements.&#160; New pilots must satisfactorily complete a
five-week training program conducted by AirNet&#146;s flight training staff prior to
assignment of pilot duties.&#160; This
training program includes flight simulator training prior to any actual flight
time in an aircraft, as well as intensive ground instruction.&#160; Additionally, new pilots gain operating
experience in a structured setting prior to assignment in order to gain a
familiarity with AirNet&#146;s route system and the unique demands of the flight
environment.&#160; In addition to FAA
requirements, pilots providing Passenger Charter services for Jetride must also
meet additional in-flight experience requirements specifically related to the
types of Learjets and Challengers operated by Jetride.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s central dispatch system ties together all components of the
air operation. Departure and arrival times are continuously updated, and
weather conditions throughout the nation are monitored. AirNet dispatchers
remain in contact with pilots, out-based hub managers, fuelers, maintenance
technicians and ground delivery personnel to identify and minimize any
potential delays in the delivery process.&#160;
AirNet also uses commercial airlines, primarily to transport shipments
during the daytime and weekend hours when its aircraft are operating under a
limited flight schedule.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Capacity management is an important factor in achieving profitable
growth of AirNet&#146;s package delivery services.&#160;
AirNet&#146;s air transportation network is positioned around a flexible
national route structure designed to facilitate late pick-up and early delivery
times, minimize delays and simplify flight scheduling.&#160; AirNet&#146;s flexible route structure allows it
to respond to the changing volume needs of its customers or to take advantage
of emerging opportunities in its Express services business.&#160; AirNet&#146;s primary hub in Columbus, Ohio, and
several mini-hubs across the nation, are located primarily in less congested
regional airports. These locations, in conjunction with AirNet&#146;s off-peak
departure and arrival times, provide easy take-off and landings, convenient
loading and unloading and fast refueling and maintenance.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet employs approximately 80 aircraft and avionics technicians in
eight separate locations across the country performing maintenance on AirNet&#146;s
fleet of aircraft.&#160; AirNet has an
in-house engine shop at the Columbus facility where some of the piston engines
are overhauled on-site, thereby reducing aircraft downtime and controlling
costs.&#160; AirNet also performs avionics
troubleshooting and repair at the Columbus facility to provide for maximum
efficiency and minimum aircraft downtime for the fleet.&#160; AirNet&#146;s aircraft maintenance center at its
Columbus hub has received ISO 9001:2000 certification.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Shipment processing</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Bank shipments are pre-sorted by bank personnel and packaged in
AirNet-supplied bags with three letter city identifier tags to show final
destination.&#160; Express shipments are
packaged in either AirNet-provided packaging or the customers&#146; packaging.&#160; Shipments transported on AirNet&#146;s air
transportation network are typically picked up by a courier and transported to
the local airport where an airbill is either scanned using bar code technology
or entered manually.&#160; Information on each
airbill pertaining to the shipper, receiver, airbill number and applicable
deadline is captured and downloaded into AirNet&#146;s computer system, where it is
available to AirNet&#146;s customer service representatives (&#147;CSRs&#148;).&#160; Upon arrival at AirNet&#146;s Columbus hub or one
of its mini-hubs, the shipment is off-loaded, sorted by destination and reloaded
onto an aircraft.&#160; At the destination
city, the shipment is off-loaded for the final time and delivered by courier to
the receiver.&#160; When delivered,
information from the airbill is once again captured and downloaded into AirNet&#146;s
computer system. Delivery information for all shipments is then available
on-line to the customers and AirNet&#146;s CSRs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">For banking customers meeting daytime banking
deadlines and Express</font> customers requiring next-flight-out timing,
shipments are typically picked up by a courier and transported via commercial
airlines or other integrators to destination cities where couriers accept the
packages and deliver them to their final destinations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Ground support</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet manages its ground delivery services through the combined use of
employees and a network of independent contractors and vendor couriers.&#160; Independent contractors and vendor couriers
perform the majority of ground delivery services, allowing AirNet to better
match its ground costs with its volume requirements.&#160; In some situations, employees are used for
ground delivery services on scheduled routes where volume requirements
economically justify employing full-time couriers.&#160; Dispatching functions related to ground
delivery services occur at both the Columbus, Ohio hub and on a regional basis
in some of the major cities served.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Mercury Business
Services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On
August 11, 2003, AirNet sold the assets of its Mercury Business Services
division to Mercury Business Services, Inc., a Delaware corporation owned by a
group that includes the original owners of the Mercury business.&#160; AirNet had acquired Mercury Business Services
in August of 1998.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">5</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Regulation</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet holds an air carrier operating certificate granted by the FAA
pursuant to Part 135 of the Federal Aviation Regulations. In addition, Jetride
holds its own air carrier operating certificate granted by the FAA pursuant to
Part 135.&#160; These certificates are of
unlimited duration and remain in effect so long as AirNet and Jetride maintain
the required standards of safety and meet the operational requirements of the
Federal Aviation Regulations.&#160; The FAA&#146;s
regulatory authority relates primarily to operational aspects of air
transportation, including aircraft standards and maintenance, personnel, and
ground facilities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The U. S. Department of Transportation (&#147;DOT&#148;) and Transportation
Security Administration (&#147;TSA&#148;) have regulatory authority concerning
operational and security concerns in transportation, respectively, including
safety, insurance and hazardous materials.&#160;
AirNet holds various operational certificates issued by these agencies,
including party status to DOT E-7060, which permits AirNet to transport higher
volumes of time-critical radioactive pharmaceuticals than is allowed by the DOT
for most carriers.&#160; Party status to DOT
E-7060 is renewed every two years, with AirNet&#146;s next renewal due August 2006.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet is also subject to Food and Drug Administration regulation of
AirNet&#146;s transportation of pharmaceuticals.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition to</font> federal
regulations, AirNet&#146;s operations are subject to various state and local
regulations, and in many instances, require permits and licenses from state
authorities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Other than as described below, AirNet believes that both AirNet and
Jetride have all permits, approvals and licenses required to conduct their
respective operations and that they are in compliance with applicable
regulatory requirements relating to their operations including all applicable
noise level regulations.&#160; Current noise
level regulations require that AirNet </font>modify its three Model 25 Learjets.&#160; AirNet can continue limited use of these
aircraft; however, AirNet intends to retire the Learjet 25&#146;s prior to the end
of the second quarter of 2005.<b><font style="font-weight:bold;">&#160; </font></b>AirNet is working proactively with
various local governments to minimize noise issues; however, future noise
pollution regulations could require the modification or replacement of other
AirNet aircraft.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
conducts a portion of its operations under an Indirect Air Carrier Standard
Security Program (&#147;IACSSP&#148;) approved by the TSA.&#160; The IACSSP permits AirNet to tender shipments
to commercial airlines.&#160; A significant
portion of AirNet&#146;s Express services packages and, to a lesser extent, a
portion of its Bank services packages, are transported on commercial airlines.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
TSA recently informed AirNet that the TSA would no longer approve AirNet&#146;s
IACSSP based upon the definition of an &#147;indirect air carrier&#148; provided under 49
CFR &#167;1540.5.&#160; Section 1540.5 excludes
from the definition of an &#147;indirect air carrier&#148; any person or entity in
possession of an FAA air carrier operating certificate.&#160; AirNet possesses a Part 135 air carrier
operating certificate issued by the FAA.&#160;
The TSA has requested that AirNet submit an application for a new IACSSP
under the name of an affiliated company.&#160;
By letter to the TSA dated February 18, 2005, AirNet has proposed to
submit an application for a new IACSSP under the name of AirNet Management,
Inc., a wholly-owned subsidiary of AirNet.&#160;
The letter sets forth the steps AirNet intends to follow to transition
commercial airline shipments to the new IACSSP and requests certain guidance
from the TSA regarding the transition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As
of the date of this Annual Report on Form 10-K, the TSA had not responded to
AirNet&#146;s request for guidance.&#160; In the
event the TSA approves the steps outlined in AirNet&#146;s February 18, 2005 letter,
AirNet Management, Inc. will submit an application to the TSA seeking approval
of a new IACSSP.&#160; Upon receipt of such
approval, AirNet will begin processing its commercial airline shipments under
the new IACSSP.&#160; It is uncertain at this
time whether the TSA will approve the proposed steps for transitioning AirNet&#146;s
commercial shipments to a new IACSSP.&#160; In
the event the TSA does not approve such steps, AirNet may need to consider
other modifications to its operating procedures in order to secure TSA approval
of an IACSSP.&#160; AirNet&#146;s current IACSSP
approval expires on August 28, 2005.&#160; If
AirNet is unable to comply with the TSA&#146;s directives with respect to the approval
and operation of a new IACSSP, AirNet may be unable to secure approval of a new
IACSSP.&#160; It is also uncertain whether the
TSA would attempt to withdraw AirNet&#146;s current IACSSP approval prior to the
August 28, 2005 expiration date.&#160; The
loss of AirNet&#146;s current IACSSP approval, or AirNet&#146;s failure to secure
approval of a new IACSSP, would have a significant and immediate adverse effect
on AirNet&#146;s operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
DOT has implemented new regulations regarding the transportation of hazardous
materials that will go into effect on April 1, 2005.&#160; These new regulations require that certain
information concerning hazardous materials shipments be maintained by the
pilot-in-command of an aircraft and be readily accessible at the airport of
departure (including any intervening airport through which the hazardous
materials are transported) and the intended airport of arrival for the duration
of the each flight leg.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A
significant portion of AirNet&#146;s operations are conducted at night at airports
where it maintains no ground operations.&#160;
Many of these airports are small and do not have fixed based operators
that are open during AirNet&#146;s night time hours of operation.&#160; Consequently, at many airports AirNet does
not currently have ground personnel or vendors on site that can receive and
maintain the hazardous materials information that is required to be readily
accessible at the airport of departure.&#160;
The new regulations will require that AirNet institute new operating
procedures and make arrangements with</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">6</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='6',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">ground
vendors and/or fixed based operators to assist AirNet in complying with the new
regulations.&#160;&#160; AirNet is in the process
of implementing these new procedures; however, AirNet anticipates that it will
not be in complete compliance with the new regulations as of April 1, 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
has submitted a request for exemption from the new hazardous materials
regulations and has proposed an alternative method of compliance.&#160; The alternative method of compliance would require
that AirNet transmit the required hazardous materials information to its
control center in Columbus, Ohio where it would be maintained and be readily
available in the event of an incident involving hazardous materials.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">There
can be no assurances the AirNet&#146;s requested exemption will be granted.&#160; In the absence of the approval of an
alternative method of compliance, AirNet will be required to continue
implementation of the procedures described above for complying with the new
regulations.&#160; Compliance with the new
regulations will likely significantly increase AirNet&#146;s cost of transporting
hazardous materials.&#160; Failure to comply
with the new regulations could reduce or otherwise restrict AirNet&#146;s ability to
transport hazardous materials, including its ability to transport radioactive
pharmaceuticals under its DOT E-7060 permit described above.&#160; AirNet is currently evaluating an additional
surcharge for transporting hazardous materials that could offset all or a portion
of the additional cost of complying with the new regulations.&#160; However, there can be no assurances that
AirNet will implement such a surcharge, or, if implemented, that AirNet&#146;s
customers will accept such surcharge or that such surcharge will fully offset
the additional costs of complying with the new regulations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Seasonality</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">See &#147;Item 7 - Management&#146;s Discussion and
Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&#148; under the heading &#147;Seasonality
and Variability in Quarterly Results&#148; of this Annual Report on Form 10-K for a
discussion of the seasonal aspects of AirNet&#146;s business, which discussion is
incorporated herein by reference.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Competition</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The air and ground courier industry is highly competitive.&#160; AirNet&#146;s primary competitor in the
transportation of cancelled checks is the Federal Reserve&#146;s Check Relay
Network. The actions of the Federal Reserve are regulated by the Monetary
Control Act, which requires the Federal Reserve to price its services at actual
cost plus a set percentage private sector adjustment factor. AirNet believes
that the purpose of the Monetary Control Act is to curtail the possibility of
predatory pricing by the Federal Reserve when it competes with the private
sector. No assurance beyond the remedies of law can be given that the Federal
Reserve will comply with the Monetary Control Act.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the private sector, there are a large number of smaller, regional
carriers that transport cancelled checks, none of which AirNet believes has a
significant interstate market share. The two largest private sector air couriers,
FedEx and United Parcel Service (&#147;UPS&#148;), both carry cancelled checks where the
deadlines being pursued fit into their existing system.&#160; AirNet does not believe that FedEx or UPS
represent significant competitors in the time-critical cancelled check market
to date.&#160; AirNet provides customized
service for its customer base, often with later pick-ups and earlier deliveries
than the large, national couriers provide.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet competes with commercial airlines and numerous other carriers in
its Express delivery business and estimates its market share in this industry
at less than 1%.&#160; AirNet believes that
this market represents a significant expansion opportunity for time-critical
shipments requiring later pick-ups or earlier deliveries than are typically provided
by major integrators and freight forwarders.&#160;
AirNet believes that it is in an excellent position to leverage the use
of its national air network system, AirNet&#146;s proprietary information technology
and its historically high on-time performance level to compete in this market.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the Passenger Charter business, AirNet competes with other
owner/operators and charter brokers of small business jets.&#160; AirNet believes its nationwide network of
maintenance and related support facilities provides added flexibility in
deploying and servicing the Passenger Charter fleet to meet customer demands.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Environmental matters</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In
2004, AirNet commenced construction of a new corporate and operational facility
on land leased from the Columbus Regional Airport Authority.&#160; Portions of the leased land, as well as
portions of the aircraft ramp, on which AirNet intends to conduct a significant
portion of its Columbus operations, contain known pollution conditions.&#160; The appropriate amended post closure plan and
no further action letters addressing these sites were obtained by AirNet from
the Columbus Regional Airport Authority prior to beginning construction.&#160; No additional pollution conditions on the
leased land have been noted to date during construction of the facility.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet believes that compliance with applicable laws and regulations
governing environmental matters has not had, and is not expected to have, a
material effect on AirNet&#146;s capital expenditures, operations or competitive
position.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">7</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Employees</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As of December 31, 2004, AirNet employed approximately 870 persons,
which includes approximately 250 pilots.&#160;
AirNet&#146;s employees are not represented by any union or covered by any
collective bargaining agreement.&#160; AirNet has
experienced no work stoppages and believes that its relationship with employees
is good.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item2Properties"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 2 -
PROPERTIES</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Operating facilities</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet leases its corporate and operational headquarters at 3939
International Gateway in Columbus, Ohio (the &#147;Port Columbus Facility&#148;).&#160; The Port Columbus Facility has 80,000 square
feet and sits on land owned by the Columbus Regional Airport Authority (the &#147;Authority&#148;).&#160; AirNet&#146;s headquarters is currently used for
operations, training, aircraft maintenance, vehicle maintenance and general and
administrative functions.&#160; In addition,
AirNet leases additional space at 555 Morrison Road in Gahanna, Ohio, for
administrative support personnel.&#160; The Gahanna
lease agreement will terminate on May 30, 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On January 20, 2004, AirNet entered into a Land Lease with the
Authority to lease approximately 8 acres located within the Rickenbacker
International Airport (&#147;Rickenbacker&#148;).&#160;
Rickenbacker is located in Franklin and Pickaway Counties, Ohio,
southeast of Columbus, Ohio, approximately fifteen miles from AirNet&#146;s current
Port Columbus Facility.&#160; AirNet is
constructing a new corporate and operational headquarters at Rickenbacker (the &#147;Rickenbacker
Facility&#148;).&#160; Construction and relocation
to the Rickenbacker Facility is anticipated to be completed in the second
quarter of 2005.&#160; Upon completion of the
Rickenbacker Facility, AirNet&#146;s current corporate and operational functions
that are conducted at the Port Columbus Facility, and the administrative
functions being conducted at 555 Morrison Road, will be consolidated at the new
Rickenbacker Facility.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On
January 20, 2004, in anticipation of AirNet&#146;s move to its new Rickenbacker
Facility, AirNet also entered into an agreement to sell its Port Columbus
Facility to the Authority for $3.9 million.&#160;
Closing of the sale of the Port Columbus Facility to the Authority took
place on December 15, 2004.&#160; Concurrently
with the sale, AirNet entered into a new lease agreement with the Authority
(the &#147;New Port Columbus Lease&#148;).&#160;
Pursuant to the New Port Columbus Lease, AirNet will lease the real
property associated with the Port Columbus Facility and the buildings and all
other improvements thereon pending completion of the construction of the
Rickenbacker Facility.&#160; The term of the
New Port Columbus Lease commenced on December&nbsp;15, 2004 and will terminate
on the earlier to occur of (i) the date AirNet moves into the Rickenbacker
Facility or (ii) August&nbsp;31, 2005.&nbsp; The New Port Columbus Lease will
be rent free until May 15, 2005 and commencing May 16, 2005, the rent will be
$30,000 per month.&nbsp; The New Port Columbus Lease is a net lease under which
AirNet is responsible for all costs of operating the Port Columbus
Facility.&#160;&#160; AirNet intends to move its
operations at the Port Columbus Facility as well as its administrative
functions to the Rickenbacker Facility during the second quarter of 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet also operates at approximately 40 additional locations
throughout the country. These locations, which are leased from unrelated third
parties, generally include office space and/or a section of the lessor&#146;s hangar
or ramp.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">8</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Fleet</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Cargo aircraft</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table shows information about AirNet&#146;s cargo aircraft
fleet used in its Delivery Services reportable segment as of December 31, 2004:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
payload in pounds for a one-hour flight plus required fuel reserves.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
range in nautical miles, assuming zero wind, full fuel and maximum payload.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(3)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
speed in knots, assuming maximum payload</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Learjet 35 and 31 are among the fastest and most reliable small jet
aircraft available in the world and meet all Stage Three noise requirements
currently being implemented across the United States.&#160; The Learjet 25 is a smaller jet aircraft with
slightly smaller payload and range capabilities.&#160; The Learjet 25 aircraft are currently being
used on a limited basis primarily as spares and will be completely phased out
of operations prior to the end of the second quarter 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Cessna Caravan Super Cargomaster aircraft is a turbo-prop aircraft.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Piper Navajo, Beech Baron and Cessna 310 are twin-engine piston
aircraft.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Passenger Charter aircraft</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
number of passengers</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
range in nautical miles, assuming zero wind, full fuel and full payload.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(3)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
speed in knots, assuming full payload</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Learjet 60 is a midsize business jet with transcontinental range
and meets all Stage Three noise requirements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Challenger is a large cabin business jet with transcontinental
range and meets all Stage Three noise requirements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Vehicles</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operated a fleet of approximately 65 ground transportation
vehicles as of December 31, 2004.&#160;&#160; Vehicles
range in size from passenger cars to full sized vans.&#160; AirNet also rents lightweight trucks for
certain weekend ground routes.&#160; In</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">9</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">2001, AirNet entered into a leasing agreement with a third party provider
and began replacing owned vehicles with leased vehicles, as replacement became
necessary.&#160; AirNet leased 41 vehicles as
of December 31, 2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item3LegalProceedings"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 3 -
LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">There are no pending legal proceedings involving AirNet other than
routine litigation incidental to its business. In the opinion of AirNet&#146;s
management, these proceedings should not, individually or in the aggregate,
have a material adverse effect on AirNet&#146;s results of operations or financial
condition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item4SubmissionOfMattersToAVote"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 4 -
SUBMISSION OF MATTERS TO A VOTE OF SECURITY HOLDERS</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">No matters were submitted to a vote of security holders during the
fourth quarter of 2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><a name="PartIi"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">PART II</font></b></a></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item5MarketForRegistrantsCommon"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 5 -

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The common shares of AirNet Systems, Inc. trade on the New York Stock

table below sets forth the high and low sales prices of the common shares
reported for the periods indicated.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
has not paid any dividends on its common shares and does not intend to pay any
dividends in the foreseeable future.&#160;
AirNet anticipates using future earnings to finance operations and
future growth and development.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
payment of any future dividends on common shares will be determined by the
AirNet Board of Directors in light of conditions then existing, including
earnings, financial condition and capital requirements, restrictions in
financing agreements, business conditions and other factors.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On March 28, 2005 there were approximately 860 record holders of AirNet&#146;s
common shares.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Neither AirNet nor any &#147;affiliated purchaser,&#148; as defined in Rule
10b-18(a)(3) under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, purchased
any common shares of AirNet during the fourth quarter of the fiscal year ended
December 31, 2004.&#160; On February 18, 2000,
AirNet announced a stock repurchase plan under which up to $3.0 million of
AirNet common shares may be repurchased from time to time.&#160; These repurchases may be made in open market
transactions or through privately negotiated transactions.&#160; As of December 31, 2004, AirNet had the
authority to repurchase approximately $0.6 million of AirNet common shares
under this stock repurchase plan.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">10</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 1</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>2001
includes a $1.0 million non-recurring charge related to the retirement
agreement of Gerald G. Mercer (see Note 7 - Related Party Transactions of the
Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8 of this Annual
Report on Form&nbsp;10-K.)</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 2</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Represents
2004 charge related to the impairment of AirNet&#146;s cargo assets and related
goodwill (See Note 2 - Impairment of Property and Equipment and Goodwill of the
Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8 of this Annual
Report on Form&nbsp;10-K.)</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 3</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Represents
2001 non-recurring charge related to the impairment of Float Control,&nbsp;Inc.&#146;s
investment in The Check Exchange System Co. partnership</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 4</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>In
August&nbsp;2003, AirNet sold the assets of its Mercury Business Services unit,
resulting in discontinued operations.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 5</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>See
Note 2 - Impairment of Property and Equipment and Goodwill of the Notes to
Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8 of this Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K
for a discussion of the 2002 charge related to the impairment of goodwill in
accordance with the adoption of SFAS No.&nbsp;142.</p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item7ManagementsDiscussionAndAna"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 7 -
MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF
OPERATION</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">General</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s Bank services revenues are expected to decline as a result of
the continuing evolution of electronic alternatives to the physical movement of
cancelled checks and other market forces.&#160;
This expected decline in Bank services revenues requires that AirNet restructure
its existing transportation network which was originally established to service
its bank customers.&#160; AirNet continues to
expand its Express and Passenger Charter services to offset the expected
decline in Bank services revenues.&#160; In
addition, AirNet continues to evaluate and adjust its aircraft mix and fleet
size in response to these changing business conditions as well as review its
ground operations for efficiencies and cost reductions.&#160; For example, Jetride increased and
diversified its fleet of owned and managed aircraft in 2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following management&#146;s discussion and analysis describes the
principal factors affecting the results of operations, liquidity and capital
resources, as well as the critical accounting policies of AirNet.&#160; This discussion should be read in conjunction
with the accompanying audited consolidated financial statements, which include
additional information about AirNet&#146;s significant accounting policies,
practices and the transactions that underlie its financial results.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Results of Operations</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
has experienced overall net revenue growth each of the last three years.&#160; This can be attributed to several factors
including increased Express Services and growth in Passenger Charter services
as well as additional fuel surcharge revenues.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
assesses its customers a fuel surcharge which is based on the Oil Price Index
Summary &#150; Columbus, Ohio (OPIS-CMH index).&#160;
As index rates increase above a set threshold, surcharge rates increase.&#160; The 2004 average annual price on the OPIS
index increased approximately 17% from the 2003 average annual price.&#160; The 2003 average annual price increased
approximately 21% from the 2002 annual price.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Bank
Services Revenues</font></i></p>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">102,626</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.3%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="7%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:7.22%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">2,718</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="8%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:8.5%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="3%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:3.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.3%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="7%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:7.22%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">773</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="8%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:8.5%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">1</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.5%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Bank
services revenues (excluding the impact of the fuel surcharge and federal
excise taxes) increased slightly during 2004 as AirNet continues to focus on
additional services for banks beyond cancelled check transportation, such as proof
of deposit and interoffice mail delivery services.&#160; Because the density of cancelled check
shipments is much greater than the typical Express shipment, profit margins on
Bank shipments are substantially higher than Express shipments after considering
cubic dimensions.&#160; From 2003 to 2004,
weekday and weekend shipment volume per flying day increased approximately 1.4%
and 5.6%, respectively.&#160; The increase in
shipment volume was offset by a decrease in the number of pounds per
shipment.&#160; Increased fuel prices during
2004 resulted in significantly higher fuel surcharge revenues compared</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">12</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='12',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">to
2003.&#160; AirNet believes that lower check
delivery volume as a result of the declining use of checks and electronic alternatives
to the physical movement of cancelled checks will contribute to a significant
reduction in Bank services revenues in future periods.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Weekday
and weekend shipment volume decreased approximately 1.3% and 9.8%,
respectively, from 2002 to 2003.&#160; Lower
check delivery volume as a result of historically low interest rates and the
declining use of checks contributed to the reduction in revenues, as did
increased competitive factors from regional carriers and transportation cost
reduction initiatives by AirNet&#146;s bank customers.&#160; The decreases in weekly shipment volume were
offset by increased fuel surcharges in 2003 as compared to 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Express
Services Revenues</font></i></p>

  <td width="23%" valign="top" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:23.0%;">
