<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 1 &#150; In August 2003, AirNet sold the assets of its Mercury Business
Services unit, resulting in discontinued operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Critical Accounting Policies and Estimates</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The preparation of financial statements in accordance with accounting
principles generally accepted in the United States requires management to adopt
accounting policies and make significant judgments and estimates to develop
amounts reflected and disclosed in the financial statements. In many cases,
there are alternative policies or estimation techniques that could be used.
AirNet maintains a thorough process to review the application of its accounting
policies and to evaluate the appropriateness of the estimates; however, even
under optimal circumstances, estimates routinely require adjustment based on
changing circumstances and the receipt of new or better information.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The policies and estimates discussed below include the financial
statement elements that are either the most judgmental or involve the selection
or application of alternative accounting policies, and are material to AirNet&#146;s
consolidated financial statements. Management has discussed the development and
selection of these critical accounting policies and estimates with the Audit
Committee of its Board of Directors and with its independent registered public
accounting firm.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Allowance for Uncollectible Accounts Receivable</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Historically, AirNet&#146;s credit losses from bad debts have not fluctuated
materially because its credit management processes have been effective. AirNet
also recognizes billing adjustments to revenue and accounts receivable for
certain discounts, money back service guarantees and billing corrections.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Estimates for credit losses and billing adjustments are regularly
updated based on historical experience of bad debts, adjustments processed,
current collection trends, and the individual assessment of customers&#146; credit
quality.&#160; Once AirNet considers all these
factors, a determination is made as to the need for a bad debt allowance.&#160; Allowances for these future adjustments
aggregated $0.9 million at December 31, 2004 and $0.5 million at December 31,
2003.&#160; AirNet considers the sensitivity
and subjectivity of these estimates to be moderate, as changes in economic
conditions and pricing arrangements can significantly affect the estimates used
to determine the allowances.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Major
Aircraft Maintenance</font></i></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Costs of major
aircraft inspections, overhauls and engine work are capitalized as incurred and
depreciated based on hours flown.&#160; The
original costs of airframes, less an estimated salvage value, are depreciated
based on the straight-line method over the estimated useful life of the
aircraft.&#160; Aircraft maintenance costs not
meeting AirNet&#146;s capitalization requirements are expensed as incurred.&#160; Approximately 85% of AirNet&#146;s Learjet 35
aircraft engines are covered under a manufacturer&#146;s Fleet Management Plan
(FMP), in which AirNet prepays certain repair and overhaul costs.&#160; These prepayments, which totaled $19.3
million and $12.7 million at December 31</font>, 2004 and 2003, respectively, are classified in fixed assets on the
consolidated balance sheet.&#160; Amortization
on these prepaid balances does not begin until major engine overhaul services</p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">22</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='22',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">have been performed, at which time the prepaid balances are reclassified
into depreciable asset categories and depreciated based</font> on hours
flown.&#160; AirNet intends to cover all of
its Lear 35 jet engines under FMP plans over the next several years as major
overhauls become due on the engines not covered under the FMP plans.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h1 align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:left;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:normal;">Property and Equipment</font></i></b></h1>

<h1 align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:left;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></i></b></h1>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s Delivery Service and
Passenger Charter service businesses are capital intensive.&#160; Over 85% of AirNet&#146;s total assets are invested
in flight equipment to serve these markets.&#160;
AirNet capitalizes those costs that meet the definition of capital
assets under accounting standards.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The depreciation or
amortization of AirNet&#146;s capital assets over their estimated useful lives, and
the determination of any salvage values, requires management to make judgments
about future events.&#160; Because AirNet
utilizes many of its capital assets over relatively long periods, management
periodically evaluates whether adjustments to estimated lives or salvage values
are necessary.&#160; The accuracy of these
estimates affects the amount of depreciation expense recognized in a period
and, ultimately, the gain or loss on the disposal of the asset.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h1 align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:left;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:normal;">Stock-Based Compensation</font></i></b></h1>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet accounts for stock
options under Accounting Principles Board Opinion No. 25, &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Accounting
for Stock Issued to Employees</font></i>&#148; (&#147;APB No. 25&#148;), which does not
require compensation costs related to stock options to be recorded in net
income, as all options granted under AirNet&#146;s stock option plan had an exercise
price equal to the market value of the underlying common shares at grant date.
SFAS No. 148. &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation -
Transition and Disclosure - an amendment of SFAS No. 123,</font></i>&#148; provides
guidance on acceptable approaches to the implementation of SFAS No. 123, and
requires more prominent disclosures of pro forma net earnings and earnings per
share determined as if the fair value method of accounting for stock options
had been applied in measuring compensation cost.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December 16, 2004, the
Financial Accounting Standards Board issued SFAS No. 123 (revised 2004), &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Share-Based Payment&#148;</font></i> (SFAS No. 123(R)), which is a revision
of SFAS No. 123, &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Accounting for Stock-Based
Compensation</font></i>&#148;.&#160; SFAS No.
123(R) supersedes APB No. 25, and amends SFAS No. 95, &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Statement of Cash Flows</font></i>.&#148;&#160; Generally, the approach in SFAS No. 123(R) is
similar to the approach described in SFAS No. 123. &nbsp;However, SFAS No.
123(R) requires all share-based
payments to employees, including grants of employee stock options, to be
recognized in the income statement based on their fair values.&#160; Pro forma disclosure will no longer be an
alternative.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">SFAS No. 123(R) must be
adopted no later than the first interim or annual period beginning after June
15, 2005.&#160; AirNet expects to adopt SFAS
No. 123(R) on July 1, 2005.&#160; The impact
of adoption of SFAS No. 123(R) cannot be predicted at this time because it will
depend on levels of share-based payments granted in the future. &nbsp;However, had
we adopted SFAS No. 123(R) in prior periods, the impact of that standard would
have approximated the impact of SFAS No. 123 as described in the disclosure of
pro forma net income (loss) and net income (loss) per share in &#147;Note 1 &#150;
Significant Accounting Policies&#148; of the Notes to Consolidated Financial
Statements included in &#147;Item 8 &#150; Financial Statements and Supplementary Data&#148;
of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.&#160;
AirNet does not anticipate that adoption of SFAS No. 123(R) will have a
material impact on its results of operations or its financial position.
&nbsp;However, SFAS No. 123(R) requires the benefits of tax deductions in
excess of recognized compensation cost to be reported as a financing cash flow,
rather than as an operating cash flow. This requirement will reduce net
operating cash flows and increase net financing cash flows in periods after the
effective date.&#160; Stock options are
further detailed in &#147;Note 1 &#150; Significant Accounting Policies&#148; and &#147;Note 5 &#150;
Incentive Stock Plans&#148; of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements
included in &#147;Item 8 &#150; Financial Statements and Supplementary Data&#148; of this
Annual Report on Form 10-K.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Self-Insurance Accruals</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet is self-insured up to certain limits for costs associated with
workers&#146; compensation claims and benefits paid under employee health care programs.
At December 31, 2004 and 2003, AirNet had total self-insurance accruals
reflected in its consolidated balance sheet of approximately $1.1 million and
$1.3 million, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The measurement of these costs requires the consideration of historical
loss experience and judgments about the present and expected levels of cost per
claim.&#160; AirNet accounts for these costs
primarily through measurement of claims outstanding and projected payments.&#160; AirNet believes its recorded obligations for
these expenses are consistently measured on an appropriate basis; however,
changes in health costs, loss development factors, accident frequency and
severity, and other factors can materially affect the estimates for these
liabilities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h1 align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:left;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:normal;">Incentive
Compensation Plans</font></i></b></h1>

<h1 align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:left;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></i></b></h1>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet maintains an incentive compensation plan with payouts tied to
the achievement of company wide earnings goals and personal/departmental
goals.&#160; Incentive compensation is
calculated as a percent of base pay, depending on participation levels, which vary
among management and staff.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">23</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='23',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Costs related to the company wide earnings portion of the plan are
accrued based on actual quarterly results.&#160;
At December 31, 2004 and 2003, no accrual existed for this portion of
the plan, as the targets were not met.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet accrues for
costs related to the personal/departmental goals portion of the plan based on
estimated achievement rates of set goals applied to individuals&#146; base pay
rates.&#160; Payouts may be made quarterly or
annually, depending on the nature of the goals.&#160;
At December 31, 2004, no amount was recorded for the personal/department
goals portion of the plan compared to $0.6 million recorded at December 31,
2003.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Income Taxes</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet accounts
for income taxes under the liability method pursuant to SFAS No. 109, &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Accounting for Income Taxes</font></i>.&#148;&#160; Under the liability method, deferred tax
liabilities and assets are determined based on the differences between the
financial reporting and tax bases of assets and liabilities using enacted tax
rates and laws that will be in effect when the differences are expected to
reverse.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At
December 31, 2004, AirNet determined that adjustments were required to AirNet&#146;s
deferred tax accounts associated with net operating loss carryforwards (NOL)
and Alternative Minimum Tax Credit carryforwards (AMT).&#160; Accounting principles generally accepted in
the United States of America require AirNet to record a valuation allowance
against these deferred tax assets if it is &#147;more likely than not&#148; that AirNet
will not be able to utilize the NOL or AMT to offset future taxes. At December
31, 2004, AirNet has recorded a valuation allowance to offset the deferred tax
assets associated with the NOL and AMT because of the uncertainty surrounding
its ability to realize such assets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Impairment of Assets and Goodwill</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
recognizes impairment losses on long-lived assets used in operations in
accordance with SFAS No. 144, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;Accounting for the
Impairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets&#148;</font></i> .&#160; AirNet recognizes impairment losses on
long-lived assets used in operations when events or changes in circumstances
indicate, in management&#146;s judgment, that the assets might be impaired and the
undiscounted cash flows estimated to be generated by those assets are less than
the carrying value of those assets.&#160; The
net carrying value of the assets not recoverable is reduced to fair market
value if lower than carrying value.&#160; In
determining the fair market value of the assets, AirNet considers market
trends, published market data, and recent transactions involving sales of
similar assets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s
long-lived assets used in its cargo operations, consisting primarily of
aircraft, spare parts and related goodwill, were determined to be impaired at
September 30, 2004.&#160; This determination
was made as a result of recent industry trends in the adoption of electronic
payment alternatives and evolving electronic alternatives to the physical
movement of cancelled checks at a more rapid pace than previously anticipated
by the industry.&#160; AirNet believes that
the effectiveness of the Check 21 Act in October 2004 will contribute to this
trend.&#160; Furthermore, recent market data
and other disclosures by the Federal Reserve confirm the accelerating decline
in cancelled check volume.&#160; AirNet&#146;s
cargo airline was originally designed, and continues to operate, primarily to
meet the needs of Bank services customers.&#160;
In the third quarter of 2004, AirNet concluded that its airline capacity
will exceed future demand, creating an impairment of the aircraft and related
assets. The impairment also reflects the overall decline in the market values
of the aircraft in its cargo fleet which have not recovered as in previous
economic cycles.&#160; AirNet determined that
the expected future undiscounted cash flows from its assets used in its
delivery services operations were less than the carrying value of those assets
and were impaired.&#160; Accordingly, a
non-cash impairment charge of $43.0 million was recorded on September 30, 2004,
using estimated aircraft fair values.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under SFAS No. 142, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets&#148;,</font></i> AirNet evaluates its goodwill for impairment annually, or more frequently if changes in circumstances indicate impairment may have occurred sooner.&#160; AirNet determined that as a result of the impairment of its long-lived assets used in its delivery services operations, the remaining goodwill assigned to the Delivery Services operations should be evaluated for potential impairment.&#160; AirNet evaluates the fair value of its goodwill related to its Delivery Services operations based upon a discounted future cash flow analysis.&#160; As a result of the impairment test, AirNet determined that its goodwill was impaired at September 30, 2004, and, accordingly, a non-cash impairment charge of $4.0 million was recorded.</font></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Rom
an" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Forward-looking statements</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The information included or incorporated by
reference in this Annual Report on Form 10-K contains various &#147;forward-looking
statements&#148; within the meaning of Section 27A of the Securities Act of 1933, as
amended, and Section 21E of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended,
including those identified by the words &#147;believe,&#148; &#147;anticipate,&#148; &#147;estimate,&#148; &#147;expect,&#148;
&#147;intend,&#148; &#147;may,&#148; &#147;plan,&#148; &#147;project&#148; and similar expressions.&#160; These forward-looking statements reflect management&#146;s
expectations and are based upon currently available data; however, actual
results are subject to future events and uncertainties, which could cause
actual results to differ from those projected in these statements.&#160; The following factors, in addition to those
included in the disclosure under the heading &#147;Risk Factors&#148; below, could cause
actual results to differ materially from those expressed in forward-looking
statements:</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">24</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>an acceleration in the migration of AirNet&#146;s Bank
customers to electronic alternatives to the physical movement of cancelled
checks;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>potential regulatory changes by the FAA, DOT and
TSA which could increase the regulation of AirNet&#146;s business, or the Federal
Reserve, which could change the competitive environment of transporting
canceled checks;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>disruptions to operations due to adverse
weather conditions, air traffic control-related constraints or aircraft
accidents;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>potential further declines in the value of
aircraft in AirNet&#146;s fleet and any related asset impairment charges;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the ability to successfully market the
Passenger Charter business in light of global changes in the commercial airline
industry;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>potential changes in locally and federally
mandated security requirements;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>increases in aviation fuel costs not fully offset
by AirNet&#146;s fuel surcharge program;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>potential cost overruns associated with the
construction of the new office and hangar facility at Rickenbacker International
Airport;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>changes in check processing and shipment patterns
of bank customers;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>acts of war and terrorist activities;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the impact of prolonged weakness in the U. S.
economy on time-critical shipment volumes;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the acceptance of AirNet&#146;s time-critical service
offerings within targeted Express markets;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>technological advances and increases in the use
of electronic funds transfers;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the availability and cost of financing required
for operations;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the impact of unusual items resulting from
ongoing evaluations of our business strategies;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; the substantial indebtedness;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>insufficient capital for future expansion; and</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .8in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>other economic, competitive and domestic and
foreign governmental factors affecting AirNet&#146;s markets, prices and other
facets of its operations.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">All forward-looking statements are expressly
qualified in their entirety by these cautionary statements.&#160; AirNet assumes no obligation or duty to
update any of the forward-looking statements included or incorporated by reference
in this Annual Report on Form 10-K except to the extent required by law.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Risk Factors</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Competition from other providers of express
air and ground delivery services may adversely affect AirNet&#146;s results of
operations and financial condition.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s Bank services compete primarily
against the Federal Reserve&#146;s Check Relay Network, which has significantly
greater financial and other resources than AirNet.&#160; The Federal Reserve is regulated by the
Monetary Control Act of 1980, which in general requires that the Federal Reserve
price its services on an actual cost basis plus a set percentage private sector
market adjustment factor.&#160; Failure by the
Federal Reserve to comply with the Monetary Control Act by pricing its services
below the required rates could have an adverse competitive impact on AirNet.&#160; In addition, the Monetary Control Act may be
amended, modified or repealed, or new legislation affecting AirNet&#146;s business
may be enacted. The market for express air and ground delivery service is
highly competitive.&#160; Although major
participants in the next-day and second-day air delivery market (such as UPS
and FedEx) have also entered the business of same day and early morning
delivery, they have not had a material adverse effect on AirNet&#146;s business to
date.&#160; However, the efforts of these
competitors could have a material adverse effect on AirNet in the future.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">25</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='25',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">The Check 21 Act or similar legislation and
electronic methods of clearing cancelled checks will have a significant adverse
effect on AirNet&#146;s revenues derived from check delivery services.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Check 21 Act, which became effective in October 2004, creates a new negotiable
instrument called a substitute check (also known as an image replacement
document or &#147;IRD&#148;) that becomes the legal equivalent of the original item.&#160; </font>The
Check 21 Act effectively removes the requirement of returning an original paper
check to the account holder&#146;s institution and requires that all financial
institutions accept an IRD in lieu of a cancelled check.&#160;&#160; The Check 21 Act and the transition in the
banking industry to electronic methods of clearing cancelled checks will
eventually replace the need for expedited air transportation services of
original cancelled checks by most of AirNet&#146;s banking customers.&#160; The Check 21 Act and electronic methods of
clearing cancelled checks will have a significant adverse affect on AirNet&#146;s
revenues derived from check delivery services.&#160;
However, it is unclear how quickly IRD&#146;s and electronic methods of
clearing cancelled checks will be implemented on a widespread basis by banking
customers and how such implementation would affect their expedited check
transportation needs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Other technological changes in the check
clearance and national payment systems may adversely affect the demand for
AirNet&#146;s Bank services from the financial services industry.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Some analysts have predicted that the
increased use of electronic funds transfers will lead to a &#147;checkless society,&#148;
which could also adversely affect the demand for AirNet&#146;s Bank services to the
financial services industry.&#160; In
addition, some financial services industry analysts have predicted the
development of various forms of imaging technology that could reduce or
eliminate the need for prompt delivery of cancelled checks.&#160; Similarly, technological advances in the
nature of &#147;electronic mail&#148; and &#147;telefax&#148; have affected the demand for on-call
delivery services by customers needing express delivery services.&#160; While none of these technological advances
has had a significant adverse impact on AirNet&#146;s business to date, these or
similar technologies, or other regulatory or technological changes in the check
clearance and national payment systems, could have an adverse affect on AirNet&#146;s
business in the future.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Government regulation significantly affects
AirNet.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s delivery operations are subject to
various federal, state and local regulations that in many instances require
permits and licenses.&#160; Failure by AirNet
to maintain required permits or licenses, or to comply with the applicable
regulations, could result in substantial fines or possible revocation of AirNet&#146;s
authority to conduct certain of its operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s flight operations are regulated by
the FAA under Part 135 of the Federal Aviation Regulations.&#160; Among other things, these regulations govern
permissible flight and duty time for aviation flight crews.&#160; The FAA has contemplated, from time to time, certain
changes in flight and duty time guidelines which, if adopted, could increase
AirNet&#146;s operating costs.&#160; These changes,
if adopted, could also require AirNet and other operators regulated by the FAA
to hire additional flight crew personnel.&#160;
In addition, Congress, from time to time, has considered various means,
including excise taxes, to raise revenues directly from the airline industry to
pay for air traffic control facilities and personnel.&#160; There can be no assurances that Congress will
not change the current federal excise tax rate or enact new excise taxes, which
could adversely affect </font>AirNet&#146;s business.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Loss of AirNet&#146;s Indirect Air Carrier Standard Security Program
approval could </font>adversely affect
AirNet&#146;s business</font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s
ability to transport packages on commercial airlines is dependent upon the TSA&#146;s
approval of AirNet&#146;s Indirect Air Carrier Standard Security Program (&#147;IACSSP&#148;).&#160; The TSA recently informed AirNet that it
would no longer approve an IACSSP for entities such as AirNet that possess an
FAA air carrier operating certificate.&#160;
The TSA has requested that AirNet submit an application for a new IACSSP
under the name of an affiliated company that does not possess an FAA air
carrier operating certificate.&#160; AirNet is
cooperating with the TSA to secure approval of a new IACSSP under the name of
an affiliated company.&#160; However, there
can be no assurances that the TSA will approve such new IACSSP.&#160; The TSA could also attempt to withdraw AirNet&#146;s
current IACSSP approval which expires on August 28, 2005.&#160; The loss of AirNet&#146;s current IACSSP approval
or AirNet&#146;s inability to secure approval of a new IACSSP would have a
significant and immediate adverse effect on AirNet&#146;s business.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Changes
in government regulations regarding the transportation of hazardous materials
may increase AirNet&#146;s costs of transporting such shipments or reduce AirNet&#146;s
ability to transport such shipments.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
DOT has implemented new regulations regarding the transportation of hazardous
materials that will go into effect on April 1, 2005.&#160; The new regulations will require that AirNet
institute new operating procedures and make arrangements with ground vendors
and/or fixed based operators to assist AirNet in complying with the new
regulations.&#160; Compliance with the new
regulations will significantly increase AirNet&#146;s cost of transporting hazardous
materials.&#160; Failure to comply with the
new regulations would reduce or otherwise restrict AirNet&#146;s ability to
transport hazardous materials, including its ability to transport radioactive
pharmaceuticals under AirNet&#146;s DOT E-7060 permit.&#160; While AirNet is seeking approval of an
alternative method of compliance which would reduce its compliance costs, there</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">26</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='26',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">can
be no assurances the alternative method of compliance will be approved.&#160; AirNet anticipates that it will not be in
complete compliance with the new regulations as of April 1, 2005.&#160; Furthermore, there can be no assurance that
the DOT will accept AirNet&#146;s operating procedures as being sufficient to meet
the requirement that the hazardous materials information be readily accessible
at the airport of departure.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Reclassification of ground couriers as employees rather than independent contractors could impact AirNet&#146;s operating costs and subject it to back taxes and other liabilities.</font></b></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet uses the services of independent contractors as couriers to pick up and deliver its packages.&#160; From time to time, federal and state authorities have sought to assert that independent contractors in the transportation industry, including independent contractors providing services similar to those utilized by AirNet, are employees rather than independent contractors. AirNet currently classifies its couriers providing services under an independent contractor agreement as independen
t contractors rather than as employees.&#160; However, there can be no assurance that federal or state authorities will not challenge this position, or that other laws or regulations, including tax laws or interpretations thereof, will not change. If, as a result of any of the foregoing, AirNet were required to pay withholding taxes and pay for and administer added employee benefits to these couriers, AirNet&#146;s operating costs would increase. Additionally, in the event of any such reclassification, AirNet could be required to pay back-up withholding with respect to amounts previously paid to such individuals and be required to pay penalties or be subject to other liabilities as a result of the incorrect classification of such individuals, such as payment of past due workers compensation and unemployment insurance premiums.</font></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Changes to current transportation security
requirements or procedures could adversely impact AirNet&#146;s ability to
efficiently conduct AirNet&#146;s air and ground operations to meet AirNet&#146;s current
delivery parameters or significantly increase costs to transact those
operations.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">Considerable focus has been placed on package
security requirements and procedures at domestic and international airports
since the September 11, 2001 tragedy and related incidents.&#160; The </font>TSA, commercial airlines, fixed based operations (where AirNet transacts a
significant portion of its aircraft loading and unloading operations) and
airport authorities are still in the process of reviewing all aspects of their
security requirements.&#160; While many
proposed changes are voluntary, many are being mandated by the TSA, the DOT and
the FAA.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2002, the TSA implemented screening procedures for
over-the-counter cargo tendered to commercial airlines. These screening
procedures have resulted in additional tender time for packages transported on
the commercial airlines in certain locations and during certain times.&#160; In addition, the TSA continues to review and
consider additional package screening requirements and changes to the vendor
screening procedures, which AirNet may need to perform on packages from its
customers.&#160;&#160;
Many commercial airlines are also adding security surcharges to
shipments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Changes at fixed base operators and by local
airport authorities could potentially limit AirNet&#146;s ramp access to its
aircraft, thereby increasing tender time from customers.&#160; Changes in chain of custody requirements
could also potentially cause AirNet to incur additional costs to staff
additional hours at certain locations.&#160;
In response to the new security-related procedures being implemented, AirNet
added a security surcharge in 2002 for its Bank and Express services
customers.&#160; Although the surcharge is
expected to help offset the increasing costs associated with security issues,
AirNet&#146;s current surcharge program may not be sufficient to cover all new costs
it may incur as additional transportation safety procedures are developed
and/or required.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As a company actively engaged in providing aviation services, AirNet is
subject to current and future regulations with which it must comply in order to
maintain its ability to provide such services.&#160;
Various governmental agencies are implementing and expanding policies,
procedures, and compliance measures to enhance the safety and security of both
domestic and international air transportation.&#160;
This increasing regulatory environment may require AirNet to change its
operational processes, modify its flight schedules, and incur additional costs
of compliance.&#160; The costs associated with
regulatory compliance could impact AirNet&#146;s financial results.&#160; AirNet&#146;s inability to comply with current or
future governmental regulations could limit or restrict AirNet&#146;s ability to
provide specific services, including but not limited to, the transportation of
hazardous materials.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Catastrophic accidents involving AirNet&#146;s
Passenger Charter aircraft could result in a significant reduction in AirNet&#146;s
business and damage to the Jetride brand.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A catastrophic accident could substantially
reduce the demand for Jetride&#146;s Passenger Charter services and, therefore,
significantly reduce its revenue.&#160; In
addition, Jetride may not be able to secure liability insurance for its
business or secure such insurance at a reasonable cost.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">27</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='27',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Environmental
concerns may arise in connection with AirNet&#146;s construction of a facility on
leased land with known pollution conditions.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
has commenced construction of the Rickenbacker Facility on land leased from the
Columbus Regional Port Authority in 2004.&#160;
Portions of the leased land, as well as portions of the aircraft ramp,
on which AirNet intends to conduct a significant portion of its Columbus
operations, contain known pollution conditions.&#160;
The appropriate amended post closure plan and no further action letters
addressing these sites have been supplied to AirNet by the Columbus Regional
Port Authority prior to beginning construction. AirNet has received the
applicable no further action letters.&#160;
Identification of additional pollution conditions on the leased land or
attached ramp or the inability of the Columbus Regional Port Authority to
provide the approved amended post closure plan could increase costs and have an
adverse affect on AirNet&#146;s ability to construct and operate the Rickenbacker
Facility.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Failure to renew party status to Department of Transportation
E-7060 would result in significant loss of Express services revenue.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
maintains party status to DOT E-7060, which permits AirNet to transport higher
volumes of radioactive pharmaceuticals than allowed by most air carriers.&nbsp;
AirNet is required to renew its party status every two years.&nbsp; Although
AirNet anticipates it will obtain its DOT E-7060 renewal at its next scheduled
renewal date in August 2006, there can be no assurances that the party status
will be extended.&nbsp; Further, there can be no assurance that AirNet can continue
to comply with all current DOT E-7060 requirements, or that such requirements
will not change in the future which would negatively affect AirNet&#146;s ability to
maintain such status.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Anti-takeover provisions may delay or prevent
an acquisition or change in control of AirNet by a third party.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Provisions of AirNet&#146;s amended articles and
code of regulations and of the Ohio Revised Code, together or separately, could
discourage potential acquisition proposals, delay or prevent a change in
control of AirNet and limit the price that certain investors might be willing
to pay in the future for the common shares.&#160;
Among other things, these provisions require certain supermajority
votes, establish advance notice procedures for shareholder nomination of
candidates for election as directors and for shareholder proposals to be
considered at shareholders&#146; meetings, eliminate cumulative voting in the
election of directors and provide that directors may only be removed from
office for cause.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s amended articles authorize the board
of directors to issue up to 10,000,000 preferred shares without further
shareholder approval, subject to any limitations prescribed by law and the
rules and regulations of the New York Stock Exchange.&#160; The preferred shares could have dividend,
liquidation, conversion and other rights and privileges that are superior or
senior to the common shares.&#160; Issuance of
preferred shares could result in the dilution of the voting power of the common
shares, adversely affect holders of the common shares in the event of
liquidation of AirNet or delay, defer or prevent a change in control of AirNet.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition, Section&nbsp;1701.831 of the
Ohio Revised Code contains provisions that require shareholder approval of any
proposed &#147;control share acquisition&#148; of any Ohio corporation at any of three
voting power thresholds:&#160; one-fifth,
one-third and a majority.&#160; Further,
Chapter&nbsp;1704 of the Ohio Revised Code contains provisions that restrict
specified business combinations and other transactions between an Ohio
corporation and interested shareholders.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">AirNet&#146;s substantial indebtedness could
adversely affect AirNet&#146;s financial health and prevent AirNet from fulfilling
its obligations.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
has a significant amount of debt.&#160; AirNet&#146;s
substantial indebtedness could: (1) require AirNet to dedicate a substantial
portion of cash flows from operating activities to payments on AirNet&#146;s
indebtedness, which would reduce the cash flows available to fund working
capital, capital expenditures and other general corporate requirements; (2)
limit AirNet&#146;s flexibility in planning for, or reacting to, changes in AirNet&#146;s
business and the industry in which AirNet operates; and (3) limit AirNet&#146;s
ability to borrow additional funds.&#160;
AirNet&#146;s liquidity and its ability to meet its current and long-term
financial obligations as they become due will be dependent upon AirNet&#146;s
financial performance, its ability to meet financial covenants in financing
agreements and its ability to replace or extend the revolving credit facility.&#160; AirNet&#146;s failure to meet these financial
covenants would have a material adverse effect on AirNet&#146;s financial position
and ability to continue operations.&#160; A
substantial portion of AirNet&#146;s revolving credit facility is funding the
Rickenbacker Facility.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">AirNet may encounter issues in documenting
and testing its internal control over financial reporting for purposes of
complying with Section 404 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet is in the process of documenting and
testing its internal control over financial reporting in order to satisfy the
requirements of Section 404 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, which requires
management&#146;s assessment of the effectiveness of AirNet&#146;s internal control over
financial reporting as of December 31, 2006 and a report by AirNet&#146;s
independent registered public accounting firm addressing management&#146;s
assessment and the effectiveness of the internal control over financial</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">28</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='28',FILE='C:\JMS\jbezawada\05-2037-1\task379652\2037-1-ba-01.htm',USER='jbezawade',CD='Mar 31 20:48 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">reporting as of that date.&#160; During the course of AirNet&#146;s testing, AirNet
may identify deficiencies and weaknesses, which AirNet may not be able to
remediate in time to meet the deadline imposed by the Sarbanes-Oxley Act for
compliance with the requirements for Section 404.&#160; If management is unable to conclude that
AirNet&#146;s internal control over financial reporting is effective at year-end
2006 or AirNet&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm is unable to
give a favorable report on management&#146;s assessment, this could have a material
adverse effect on AirNet&#146;s reputation, financial condition and market price of
AirNet&#146;s common shares.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item7aQuantitativeAndQualitativeD"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 7A -
QUANTITATIVE AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Inflation and Interest Rates</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet is exposed to certain market risks from transactions that are
entered into during the normal course of business.&#160; AirNet&#146;s primary market risk exposure relates
to interest rate risk.&#160; At December 31,
2004, AirNet had a $30.5 million outstanding balance under its Amended Credit
Agreement (described above in &#147;Item 7 &#150; Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of
Financial Condition and Results of Operation&#148;) subject to market rate changes
in interest.&#160; The Amended Credit
Agreement </font>bears
interest, at AirNet&#146;s option, at (a) a fixed rate equal to LIBOR plus a margin
determined by AirNet&#146;s leverage ratio as defined in the Amended Credit
Agreement, or (b) a floating rate based on the greater of the sum of (i) the
prime rate established by The Huntington National Bank from time to time plus a
margin determined by AirNet&#146;s leverage ratio as defined in the Amended Credit
Agreement and (ii) the sum of 0.5% plus the federal funds rate in effect from
time to time.&#160; Assuming borrowing levels
at December 31, 2004, a one hundred basis point change in interest rates would
impact net interest expense by approximately $195,000 per year.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Following
the effectiveness of the Amended Credit Agreement dated May 28, 2004, AirNet
paid off three secured term loans which had been secured by aircraft. One of
those loans had an interest rate swap agreement associated with it.&#160; This interest rate swap agreement with a
notional amount of $3.0 million and a fixed rate of 4.25% plus a margin based
on AirNet&#146;s funded debt ratio remains in place.&#160;
At December 31, 2004, the aggregate fair value of the interest rate swap
was approximately ($15,000).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Fuel
Surcharge</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
assesses its customers a fuel surcharge which is based on the Oil Price Index
Summary &#150; Columbus, Ohio (OPIS-CMH Index).&#160;
As index rates increase above a set threshold, surcharge rates increase.&#160; AirNet&#146;s fuel surcharge program helps offset
timing differences between market prices and the OPIS-CMH index used to
determine surcharge rates.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">29</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item8_124015"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 8 -</font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;"> FINANCIAL STATEMENTS AND SUPPLEMENTARY DATA</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="ReportOfIndependentRegisteredPubl_170417"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Shareholders and Board of Directors</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of AirNet
Systems, Inc. as of December&nbsp;31, 2004 and 2003, and the related
consolidated statements of operations, shareholders&#146; equity, and cash flows for
each of the three years in the period ended December&nbsp;31, 2004.&#160; Our audits also included the financial
statement schedule&nbsp;listed in the Index at Item 15 (a) 2.&#160; These financial statements and schedule&nbsp;are
the responsibility of the management of AirNet Systems, Inc.&#160; Our responsibility is to express an opinion
on these financial statements and schedule&nbsp;based on our audits.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public
Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require
that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether
the financial statements are free of material misstatement.&#160; We were not engaged to perform an audit of
the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting.&#160; Our audit included consideration of internal
control over financial reporting as a basis for designing audit procedures that
are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an
opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial
reporting. Accordingly, we express no such opinion.&#160; An audit also includes examining, on a test
basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial
statements, assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates
made by management, and evaluating the overall financial statement
presentation.&#160; We believe that our audits
provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In our opinion, the financial statements referred to above present
fairly, in all material respects, the consolidated financial position of AirNet
Systems, Inc. at December&nbsp;31, 2004 and 2003, and the consolidated results
of its operations and its cash flows for each of the three years in the period
ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, in conformity with U.S. generally accepted
accounting principles.&#160; Also, in our
opinion, the related financial statement schedule, when considered in relation
to the basic financial statements taken as a whole, presents fairly in all
material respects the information set forth therein.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As discussed in Note 2, in 2002 AirNet Systems, Inc. changed its method
of accounting for goodwill in accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting
Standards No. 142, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Goodwill and Other
Intangible Assets</font></i>.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>
