<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="NotesToConsolidatedFinancialState_170451"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENT</font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">S</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">1.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Significant
Accounting Policies</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc. and its subsidiaries (&#147;AirNet&#148;, the &#147;Company&#148;)
operate a fully integrated national air transportation network which provides
delivery service for time-critical shipments for customers in the U.S. banking
industry and other industries requiring the express delivery of packages.&#160; AirNet also offers passenger charter services
and retail aviation fuel sales and related ground services for customers at its
Columbus, Ohio facility.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Basis of Presentation</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The accompanying consolidated financial statements include the accounts
of AirNet Systems, Inc. and its subsidiaries.&#160;
All significant intercompany accounts and transactions have been
eliminated.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Preparation of the consolidated financial statements in conformity with
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America
requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the amounts
reported in the consolidated financial statements and accompanying notes.&#160; Actual results could differ from those
estimates.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain 2003 and 2002 balances have been reclassified to conform with
the 2004 presentation.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Revenue Recognition</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Revenue on Express services and Bank services is recognized when the
packages are delivered to their destination. Revenue related to Passenger
Charter services is recognized from both owned and managed aircraft in the
period in which the charter services are completed.&#160; Revenue on fixed based operations within
Aviation services is recognized when the maintenance services are complete or
fuel is delivered.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet receives advance payments from some customers.&#160; These advances secure space on AirNet&#146;s air
transportation network during the period for which the payment applies.&#160; These prepaid revenues are classified as
deferred revenue and revenue is recognized based on the number of flying days
elapsed.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Cash and Cash Equivalents</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Cash and cash equivalents consist of highly liquid investments which
are unrestricted as to withdrawal or use, and which have an original maturity
of three months or less.&#160; Cash
equivalents are stated at cost, which approximates market value.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Accounts Receivable</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet performs periodic credit evaluations of its customers&#146; financial
condition and generally does not require collateral.&#160; AirNet establishes an allowance for doubtful
accounts based upon factors surrounding the credit risks of specific customers,
historical trends and other information.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Inventory</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Inventory is valued at the lower of cost (weighted average method) or
market.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Property and Equipment</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Property and equipment are stated at cost.&#160; Costs of major aircraft inspections,
overhauls and engine work are capitalized as incurred and depreciated based on
hours flown.&#160; The original costs of
airframes, other flight equipment and other property and equipment (primarily
furniture and equipment, leasehold improvements, computer related hardware and
software and vehicles) are depreciated based on the straight-line method over
the estimated useful lives of the assets as summarized below.&#160; Aircraft maintenance costs not meeting AirNet&#146;s
capitalization requirements are expensed as incurred.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet evaluates the remaining salvage values and depreciable lives of
its property and equipment as conditions dictate. In 2003, AirNet reduced the
salvage values and shortened the depreciable lives for its fleet of Cessna 310
and Learjet 25 aircraft as a response to changes in the projected usage for its
fleet.&#160; This change in estimate resulted
in approximately $489,000 of additional depreciation expense in 2003 compared
to 2002.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">35</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The engines of approximately 85% of AirNet&#146;s Learjet 35 aircraft
engines are covered under a Fleet Management Plan (FMP), in which AirNet
prepays certain repair and overhaul costs.&#160;
These prepayments, which totaled approximately $19.3 million and $12.7
million at December&nbsp;31, 2004 and 2003, respectively, are classified in
fixed assets on the consolidated balance sheet.&#160;
Amortization on these prepaid balances does not begin until major engine
overhaul services have been performed, at which time the prepaid balances are
reclassified into depreciable asset categories and depreciated based on hours
flown.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Property and equipment consisted of the following at December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="64%" valign="top" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:64.96%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Less
  accumulated depreciation</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="15%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:15.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">27,062,000</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="15%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:15.02%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">99,625,000</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="64%" valign="top" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:64.96%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Net property
  and equipment</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.52%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">$</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="13%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:13.48%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">106,816,000</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.52%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="13%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:13.5%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">125,102,000</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
recognizes impairment losses on long-lived assets used in operations in
accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting Standards (SFAS) No. 144, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;Accounting for the Impairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets&#148;</font></i>
(SFAS No. 144).&#160; AirNet recognizes
impairment losses on long-lived assets used in operations when events or
changes in circumstances indicate, in management&#146;s judgment, that the assets
might be impaired and the undiscounted cash flows estimated to be generated by
those assets are less than the carrying value of those assets.&#160; The net carrying value of the assets not
recoverable is reduced to fair market value if lower than carrying value.&#160; In determining the fair market value of the
assets, AirNet considers market trends, published market data, and recent
transactions involving sales of similar assets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Self-Insurance Accruals</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet is self-insured up to certain limits for costs associated with
workers&#146; compensation claims and benefits paid under employee health care
programs. The measurement of these costs requires the consideration of
historical loss experience and judgments about the present and expected levels
of cost per claim.&#160; AirNet accounts for
these costs primarily through measurement of claims outstanding and projected
payments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h1 align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:left;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:normal;">Incentive Compensation Plans</font></i></b></h1>

<h1 align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:left;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">&nbsp;</font></i></b></h1>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
maintains an incentive compensation plan with payouts tied to the achievement
of company wide earnings goals and personal/departmental goals.&#160; Incentive compensation is calculated as a
percent of base pay, depending on participation levels, which vary among
management and staff.&#160; AirNet accrues for
costs related to the personal/departmental goals portion of the plan based on
estimated achievement rates of set goals applied to individuals&#146; base pay
rates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Income Taxes</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet accounts for income taxes under the liability method pursuant to
SFAS No. 109, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;Accounting for Income Taxes.&#148;</font></i>&#160; Under the liability method, deferred tax
liabilities and assets are determined based on the differences between the
financial reporting and tax bases of assets and liabilities using enacted tax
rates and laws that will be in effect when the differences are expected to
reverse.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At
December&nbsp;31, 2004, AirNet determined that adjustments were required to
AirNet&#146;s deferred tax accounts associated with net operating loss carryforwards
(NOL) and Alternative Minimum Tax Credit carryforwards (AMT).&#160; Accounting principles generally accepted in
the United States of America require AirNet to record a valuation allowance
against these deferred tax assets if it is &#147;more likely than not&#148; that AirNet
will not be able to utilize the NOL or AMT to offset future taxes.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2004, AirNet has
recorded a valuation allowance of $5.7 million to offset the deferred tax
assets associated with the NOL and AMT because of the uncertainty surrounding
its ability to realize such assets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h3 style="font-style:italic;font-weight:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Goodwill</font></i></h3>

<h3 style="font-style:italic;font-weight:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;">&nbsp;</font></i></h3>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet adopted SFAS No. 141, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;</font>Business Combinations&#148;,</i> and SFAS
No. 142, &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Goodwill and Other Intangible
Assets&#148;</font></i>, effective January&nbsp;1, 2002.&#160; SFAS No. 141 requires business combinations
completed after June&nbsp;30, 2001, to be accounted for using the purchase
method of accounting and changes the criteria for recording intangible assets
apart from goodwill.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">SFAS No. 142 requires that goodwill and indefinite-lived intangible
assets no longer be amortized, but instead be evaluated for impairment on a &#147;reporting
unit&#148; basis annually, or more frequently if changes in circumstances indicate
impairment may have occurred sooner.&#160; A
reporting unit is the operating segment unless, for businesses within that
operating segment,</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">36</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='36',FILE='C:\JMS\Snagara\05-2037-1\task379752\2037-1-ba-02.htm',USER='kkthiyagarajan',CD='Mar 31 21:12 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">discrete financial information is prepared and regularly reviewed by
management, in which case such a component business is the reporting unit.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The impairment test is conducted by comparing the fair value of the
reporting unit, primarily determined by computing the future discounted cash
flows expected to be generated by the reporting unit, with its carrying value
and if the carrying value exceeds the fair value, goodwill may potentially be
impaired.&#160; If there is potential
impairment, the fair value of the reporting unit is allocated to its assets and
liabilities in a manner similar to a purchase price allocation in order to
determine the implied fair value of the reporting unit goodwill.&#160; This implied fair value is then compared with
the carrying amount of the reporting unit goodwill, and if the implied fair
value is less, an impairment loss is recognized.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Financial Instruments</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The fair value of AirNet&#146;s financial instruments approximated their
carrying value at December&nbsp;31, 2004 and 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Derivatives</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet has been party to various interest rate swap agreements with
banks as a hedge against the interest rate risk associated with borrowing at
variable rates.&#160; These swap agreements
are accounted for as cash flow hedges.&#160;
The objective of the hedge is to eliminate the variability of cash flows
in the interest rate payments on the variable rate debt.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In February&nbsp;2002, AirNet entered into a five-year interest rate
swap agreement with a bank relative to a $3.0 million term loan.&#160; </font>Following the effectiveness of the Amended Credit Agreement dated May
28, 2004, and as discussed in Note 4, AirNet paid off three secured term loans
which had been secured by aircraft. &#160;This
interest rate swap agreement with a notional amount of $3.0 million and a fixed
rate of 4.25% plus a margin based on AirNet&#146;s funded debt ratio remains in
place.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2004, the
aggregate fair value of the interest rate swap was approximately ($15,000).</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet accounts for it swap agreements under SFAS No. 133, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;Accounting for Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities&#148;</font></i>,
and its amendments, SFAS Nos. 137 and 138.&#160;
The statements require AirNet to recognize all derivatives on the
balance sheet at fair value.&#160; Derivatives
that are not hedges are adjusted to fair value through income.&#160; If the derivative is a hedge, depending on
the nature of the hedge, changes in the fair value of the derivative are either
offset against the change in fair value of assets, liabilities, or firm
commitments through earnings or recognized in other comprehensive income until
the hedged item is recognized in earnings.&#160;
The ineffective portion of a derivative&#146;s change in fair value is
immediately recognized in earnings.&#160; In
2004, AirNet recognized comprehensive income of approximately $30,000, net of
tax, related to the swaps, compared to $24,000 of comprehensive income, net of
tax, in 2003.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2004
and 2003, the aggregate fair value of the interest rate swaps was approximately
($15,000) and ($65,000), respectively, and is recorded in other liabilities on
the consolidated balance sheets.&#160; The
ineffective portion of the change in fair value is immaterial for all years
presented.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Stock-Based Compensation</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2004, AirNet had two stock-based employee
compensation plans, which are described more fully in Note 5.&#160; AirNet has accounted for the plans under the
recognition and measurement principles of APB Opinion No. 25, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;</font>Accounting for Stock
Issued to Employees&#148;,</i> and related interpretations.&#160; No stock-based employee compensation cost is
reflected in net income, as all options granted under the plans have an
exercise price equal to the market value of the underlying common shares on the
date of grant.&#160; Pro forma information
regarding net income and earnings per share is required by SFAS No. 148, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;</font>Accounting for
Stock-Based Compensation &#150; Transition and Disclosure&#148; </i>(SFAS No. 148), and has been
determined as if AirNet had accounted for its employee stock options under the
fair value method of SFAS No. 123, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;</font>Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation&#148;
</i>(SFAS No. 123).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December&nbsp;16, 2004,
the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) issued SFAS No. 123 (revised
2004), &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Share-Based Payment&#148; </font></i>(SFAS No. 123(R)),
which is a revision of SFAS No. 123.&#160;
SFAS No. 123(R) supersedes APB Opinion No. 25, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;</font>Accounting for Stock Issued to Employees&#148;</i>,
and amends SFAS No. 95, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;</font>Statement of Cash Flows</i>.<i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#148; </font></i>&#160;Generally, the
approach in SFAS No. 123(R) is similar to the approach described in SFAS No.
123. &nbsp;However, SFAS No. 123(R) requires
all share-based payments to employees, including grants of employee stock
options, to be recognized as expense in the income statement based on their
fair values.&#160; Pro forma disclosure will no
longer be an alternative.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">SFAS No. 123(R) must be
adopted no later than the first interim or annual period beginning after June&nbsp;15,
2005.&#160; AirNet expects to adopt SFAS No.
123(R) on July&nbsp;1, 2005.&#160; SFAS No.
123(R) permits companies to adopt its requirements using one of two methods:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">1.</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>A
&#147;modified prospective&#148; method in which compensation cost is recognized
beginning with the effective date (a) based on the requirements of SFAS No.
123(R) for all share-based payments granted after the effective date and (b)
based on the requirements of SFAS No. 123 for all awards granted to employees
prior to the effective date of SFAS No. 123(R) that remain unvested on the
effective date.</p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">37</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='37',FILE='C:\JMS\Snagara\05-2037-1\task379752\2037-1-ba-02.htm',USER='kkthiyagarajan',CD='Mar 31 21:12 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">2.</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>A
&#147;modified retrospective&#148; method which includes the requirements of the modified
prospective method described above, but also permits entities to restate
financial statements based on the amounts previously recognized under SFAS No.
123 for purposes of pro forma disclosures either (a) all prior periods
presented or (b) prior interim periods of the year of adoption.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet plans to adopt SFAS
No. 123(R) using the modified prospective method.&#160; The impact of adoption of SFAS No. 123(R)
cannot be predicted at this time because it will depend on levels of
share-based payments granted in the future. However, had we adopted SFAS No.
123(R) in prior periods, the impact of that standard would have approximated
the impact of SFAS No. 123 as described in the disclosure of pro forma net
income (loss) and net income (loss) per share below.&#160; AirNet does not anticipate that adoption of
SFAS No. 123(R) will have a material impact on its results of operations or its
financial position. &nbsp;However, SFAS No. 123(R) also requires that the
benefits of tax deductions in excess of recognized compensation cost be
reported as a financing cash flow, rather than as an operating cash flow.
&nbsp;This requirement will reduce net operating cash flows and increase net
financing cash flows in periods after the effective date. &nbsp;While AirNet
cannot estimate what those amounts will be in the future (because they depend
on, among other things, when employees exercise stock options), the amount of
operating cash flows recognized in prior periods for such excess tax deductions
were not material.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet adopted the
fair-value-based method of accounting for share-based payments effective January&nbsp;1,
2003 using the &#147;modified prospective method&#148; described in SFAS No. 148.&#160; Currently, AirNet uses the Black-Scholes
option pricing model to estimate the value of stock options granted to
employees for purposes of computing the pro forma disclosures required by SFAS
No. 123.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The fair value of these options was estimated at the date of grant
using the Black-Scholes option pricing model with the following weighted
average assumptions for the years ended December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="80%" style="border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:.5in;width:80.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="56%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:56.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The weighted average fair value of options granted was
$2.15, $2.37 and $4.21 in the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, 2003 and
2002, respectively.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

value recognition provisions of SFAS No. 123 to stock-based employee
compensation.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Supplemental Cash Flow Data</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Cash paid for interest was $2,414,000, $1,584,000, and $1,433,000 for
the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, 2003, and 2002, respectively.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2004, AirNet capitalized
approximately $0.1 million in interest related to the construction of its new
Rickenbacker office and hangar facility.&#160;
AirNet paid $208,000, $459,000, and $1,216,000 and received $62,000,
$1,332,000, and $51,000 for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, 2003, and
2002, respectively, related to income taxes.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">38</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='38',FILE='C:\JMS\Snagara\05-2037-1\task379752\2037-1-ba-02.htm',USER='kkthiyagarajan',CD='Mar 31 21:12 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Impairment
of Property and Equipment and Goodwill</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
recognizes impairment losses on long-lived assets used in operations in
accordance with SFAS No. 144 &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Accounting for the
Impairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets&#148;</font></i> (SFAS No. 144).&#160; AirNet recognizes impairment losses on
long-lived assets used in operations when events or changes in circumstances
indicate, in management&#146;s judgment, that the assets might be impaired and the
undiscounted cash flows estimated to be generated by those assets are less than
the carrying value of those assets.&#160; The
net carrying value of the assets not recoverable is reduced to fair market
value if lower than carrying value.&#160; In
determining the fair market value of the assets, AirNet considers market
trends, published market data, and recent transactions involving sales of
similar assets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s
long-lived assets used in its cargo operations, consisting primarily of
aircraft, spare parts and related goodwill, were determined to be impaired at September&nbsp;30,
2004.&#160; This determination was made as a
result of recent industry trends in the adoption of electronic payment
alternatives and evolving electronic alternatives to the physical movement of
cancelled checks at a more rapid pace than previously anticipated by the industry.&#160; AirNet believes that the effectiveness of the
Check 21 Act in October&nbsp;2004 will contribute to this trend.&#160; Furthermore, recent market data and other
disclosures by the Federal Reserve confirm the accelerating decline in
cancelled check volume.&#160; AirNet&#146;s cargo
airline was originally designed, and continues to operate, primarily to meet
the needs of Bank Services customers.&#160; In
the third quarter of 2004, AirNet concluded that its airline capacity will
exceed future demand, creating an impairment of the aircraft and related
assets. The impairment also reflects the overall decline in the market values
of the aircraft in its cargo fleet which have not recovered as in previous
economic cycles.&#160; AirNet determined that the
expected future undiscounted cash flows from its assets used in its Delivery Services
operations were less than the carrying value of those assets and were
impaired.&#160; Accordingly, a non-cash
impairment charge of $43.0 million was recorded on September&nbsp;30, 2004,
using estimated aircraft fair values.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under SFAS No. 142, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets&#148;,</font></i> AirNet evaluates its goodwill for impairment annually, or more frequently if changes in circumstances indicate impairment may have occurred sooner.&#160; AirNet determined that as a result of the impairment of its long-lived assets used in its Delivery Services operations, the remaining goodwill assigned to the Delivery Services operations should be evaluated for potential impairment.&#160; AirNet evaluates the fair value of its goodwill related to its Delivery Services operations based upon a discounted future cash flow analysis.&#160; As a result of the impairment test, AirNet determined that its goodwill was impaired at September&nbsp;30, 2004, and, accordingly, a non-cash impairment charge of $4.0 million was recorded.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Following
is a progression of goodwill for the years ended December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet adopted SFAS No. 142 as of January&nbsp;1, 2002.&#160; AirNet performed the transitional goodwill
impairment test using the two-step process prescribed in SFAS No. 142 with a
measurement date of January&nbsp;1, 2002. The first step is a screen of potential
impairment, while the second step measures the amount of the impairment, if
any. AirNet performed the first of the required transitional goodwill
impairment tests in the second quarter of 2002. AirNet performed the second of
the required transitional goodwill impairment tests in the fourth quarter of
2002.&#160; Under SFAS No. 142, an impairment
charge resulting from the transitional impairment tests was reflected as the
cumulative effect of a change in accounting principle in the first quarter of
2002.&#160; Based on the results of its
transitional goodwill impairment test, AirNet recognized an impairment loss,
net of tax, of $1,868,000, for goodwill related to the Mercury Business
Services unit as a cumulative effect of a change in accounting principle in the
first quarter of 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">3.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Segment
Reporting</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
operates a fully integrated national air transportation network and has
determined that its reportable segments are based on AirNet&#146;s methods of
internal reporting and management structure.&#160;
The Company&#146;s reportable segments are Delivery Services, which provides
delivery service of time-critical shipments for Bank customers and other
Express customers, and Passenger Charter Services.&#160; AirNet evaluates segment performance based on
several factors, of which the primary financial measure is contribution
margin.&#160; Contribution margin represents
the net revenues of the reporting segment less costs and expenses directly
associated with the reporting segments.&#160;
The most significant difference between contribution margin and income
(loss) from operations is selling, general and administrative expenses that are
not directly associated with a reporting segment.&#160; The accounting policies used for segment
reporting are the same as those described in the summary of Significant
Accounting Policies used for consolidated reporting.&#160; There were no material</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">39</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

of revenues or transfers between reportable segments.&#160; Financial information for the fiscal year
ended December&nbsp;31 by business segment follows:</font></p>

  <td width="13%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:13.5%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">153,273,000</font></p>
  </td>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">4.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Notes
Payable</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Term Notes and Revolving Credit Facility</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In September&nbsp;2002,
AirNet entered into a $35 million unsecured revolving credit facility and a
five-year $20.0 million unsecured term loan (collectively, the &#147;Credit
Agreement&#148;).&#160; The term loan requires
quarterly installments of $1.0 million</font> beginning in December 2002 and continuing
through September&nbsp;30, 2007.&#160;
As of December&nbsp;31, 2003, there was $6.5 million available under the
credit facility.&#160; The revolving credit facility under the Credit Agreement was originally
scheduled to expire on September&nbsp;30, 2005 and the secured term loan was to
mature on September&nbsp;30, 2007.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On May 28, 2004, AirNet and
its lenders amended the terms and conditions of the Credit Agreement (the &#147;Amended
Credit Agreement&#148;). The Amended Credit Agreement was further amended by the
First Change in Terms Agreement and the Second Change in Terms Agreement as
described below.&#160; The Amended Credit
Agreement is secured by a first lien on all of the property of AirNet and its
subsidiaries, other than any interest in real estate and certain excluded fixed
assets.&#160; AirNet also pledged the stock
and interests of its subsidiaries to secure the loans under the Amended Credit
Agreement, and each of AirNet&#146;s subsidiaries guaranteed AirNet&#146;s obligations
under the Amended Credit Agreement.&#160; The
Amended Credit Agreement permits AirNet and its subsidiaries to incur other
indebtedness for the purpose of purchasing or refinancing aircraft and related
tangible fixed assets, subject to certain annual limitations.&#160; The Amended Credit Agreement contains
limitations on operating leases, indebtedness, significant corporate changes
including mergers and sales of assets, investments in subsidiaries and
acquisitions, liens, capital expenditures, transactions with affiliates, sales
of accounts receivable, sale and leaseback transactions and other off-balance
sheet liabilities, contingent obligations and hedging transactions. The Amended
Credit Agreement also contains certain financial covenants that require AirNet
to maintain a minimum consolidated tangible net worth and to not exceed certain
fixed charge coverage and leverage ratios specified in the Amended Credit
Agreement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Amended Credit Agreement
provides for a secured revolving credit facility of up to $35.0 million and a
secured term loan in the aggregate amount of $14.0 million.&#160; The amount of revolving loans available under
the Amended Credit Agreement is limited to a borrowing base equal to the
aggregate of 80% of eligible accounts receivable, plus 50% of eligible
inventory, plus 70% of the market value of certain fixed assets, reduced by the
aggregate amount of AirNet&#146;s outstanding letters of credit.&#160; The Amended Credit Agreement bears interest,
at AirNet&#146;s option, at (a) a fixed rate equal to LIBOR plus a margin determined
by AirNet&#146;s leverage ratio as defined in the Amended Credit Agreement, or (b) a
floating rate based on the greater of the sum of (i) the prime rate established
by The Huntington National Bank from time to time plus a margin determined by
AirNet&#146;s leverage ratio and (ii) the sum of 0.5% plus the federal funds rate in
effect from time to time.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,
2004, as a result of the various timing and duration of short-term debt
maturities, the interest rate was between 4.5% and 5.5%.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As of December&nbsp;31, 2004,
$19.5 million and $11.0 million were outstanding under the secured revolving
credit facility and secured term loan, respectively.&#160; In addition, AirNet had $1.7 million in
letters of credit outstanding on such date related to insurance programs, which
reduced the amount available under the revolving credit facility.&#160; After giving effect to the Second Change in
Terms Agreement discussed below, AirNet had approximately $8.8 million
available to borrow on its secured revolving credit facility as of December&nbsp;31,
2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As a result of the impairment
charge recorded in September&nbsp;2004 as described in Note 2, AirNet was not
in compliance with the fixed charge coverage ratio and the leverage ratio
calculated as of September&nbsp;30, 2004, and AirNet would not have been in
compliance with the minimum consolidated tangible net worth requirement as of December&nbsp;31,
2004.&#160; On November&nbsp;12, 2004, AirNet
and its lenders under the Amended Credit Agreement agreed to modify the terms
and conditions of the Amended Credit Agreement (the &#147;First Change in Terms
Agreement&#148;).&#160; The First Change in Terms
Agreement modified the fixed charge coverage ratio, the leverage ratio, and the
minimum consolidated tangible net worth</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">41</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='41',FILE='C:\JMS\Snagara\05-2037-1\task379752\2037-1-ba-02.htm',USER='kkthiyagarajan',CD='Mar 31 21:12 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">financial covenants in such a
manner that, on a going-forward basis, the impairment charge, in and of itself,
would not cause a default of these financial covenants in the future.&#160; At the same time as the First Change of Terms
Agreement was entered into, AirNet and its lenders executed a waiver of any
defaults or potential defaults under the Amended Credit Agreement which
occurred, or may have occurred, as a result of AirNet&#146;s failure to comply with
the foregoing financial covenants due to the impairment charge.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On March&nbsp;24, 2005,
AirNet and its lenders entered into a &#147;Second Change in Terms Agreement&#148; that
further modified the terms and conditions of the Amended Credit Agreement.&#160; In accordance with the Second Change in Terms
Agreement, AirNet prepaid in full the remaining $11.0 balance outstanding on
its secured term loan.&#160; Upon the
prepayment of the term loan, the term loan portion of the Amended Credit
Agreement was terminated.&#160; In addition,
the revolving credit facility under the Amended Credit Agreement was reduced
from $35.0 million to $30.0 million.&#160; In
the event AirNet secures permanent financing on all or a portion of its
Rickenbacker Facility, the revolving credit facility will be reduced from $30.0
million to $25.0 million.&#160; Under the
Second Change in Term Agreement, the term of the revolving credit facility was
extended from September&nbsp;30, 2005 to October&nbsp;15, 2006.&#160; The December 31, 2004 Balance Sheet gives effect
to the Second Change in Terms Agreement entered into on March 24, 2005.&#160; The Second Change in Terms Agreement also
provided for the release of certain fixed assets that were securing the loans
under the Amended Credit Facility and modified certain other financial
covenants.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Other Term Notes</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On March&nbsp;24, 2005,
AirNet entered into a three-year term loan totaling $11.0 million with a fixed
interest rate of 8.12%.&#160; This term loan
is secured by seven Cessna Caravans and nine LearJet 35&#146;s from AirNet&#146;s cargo
aircraft fleet with a combined net book value as of December&nbsp;31, 2004 of
approximately $19.9 million.&#160; The
aircraft securing this loan were released from the collateral securing the
loans under Amended Credit Agreement in accordance with the Second Change in
Terms Agreement.&#160; The proceeds from this
term loan were used to prepay in full AirNet&#146;s term loan under the Amended
Credit Facility as described above.&#160; The
December 31, 2004 Balance Sheet reflects the reclassification of approximately $22.4
million from current to long term notes payable as a result of the extension of
the Amended Credit Facility under the Second Change in Terms Agreement and the
financing of the cargo aircraft described above.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During the
second quarter of 2004, Jetride entered into four seven-year term loans
totaling $22.5 million with fixed interest rates of approximately 6.7%.&#160; In July 2004, Jetride financed two additional
passenger charter Learjet 60&#146;s for the Passenger Charter fleet at $5.0 million
each with fixed rates of approximately 6.5% for a total of $32.5 million in
financing related to AirNet&#146;s Passenger Charter services.&#160; As of December 31, 2004, there was $31.7
million outstanding under all six loans.&#160;
These term loans are secured by aircraft used in the Passenger Charter
fleet with a net book value of $40.0 million at December 31, 2004.&#160; Each of the term loans is guaranteed by
AirNet. &#160;AirNet incurred $1.2 million in
interest expense in 2004 related to the financing of the nine Passenger Charter
aircraft under all six loans.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Aggregate future maturities of long-term debt as of December&nbsp;31,
2004 are as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet also maintains standby letters of credit totaling $1,700,000
with a bank related to its insurance policy agreements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">5.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Incentive
Stock Plans</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On June&nbsp;4, 2004, the shareholders of AirNet Systems, Inc. approved
the AirNet Systems, Inc. 2004 Stock Incentive Plan (the &#147;2004 Plan&#148;), for
employees of AirNet and its subsidiaries and non-employee directors of
AirNet.&#160; The 2004 Plan authorizes the
granting of incentive and non-qualified stock options, restricted stock, stock
appreciation rights, and performance shares to be paid in common shares and
performance units to be paid in cash (collectively, &#147;2004 Plan Awards&#148;).&#160; In addition, the 2004 Plan provides for the
granting of options to purchase common shares of AirNet Systems, Inc. at up to
a 15% discount through payroll deductions by employees of AirNet and its
subsidiaries (the &#147;2004 Stock Purchase Program&#148;).&#160; The maximum number of common shares available
for issuance under the 2004 Plan is 1,000,000.&#160;
The 2004 Plan is administered by the Compensation Committee of the Board
of Directors, which determines the terms and conditions applicable to the 2004
Plan Awards, other than options automatically granted to non-employee directors
in accordance with the terms of the 2004 Plan.&#160;
The Compensation Committee also has the authority to establish
administrative rules and regulations regarding the term of each offering under
the 2004 Stock Purchase Plan.&#160; No 2004
Plan Awards have been granted.&#160; In 2004, 17,153
common shares were issued under the 2004 Stock Purchase Program to AirNet
employees.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 1996, AirNet Systems, Inc. adopted the AirNet Systems, Inc. 1996
Incentive Stock Plan (as amended and restated, the &#147;1996 Plan&#148;).&#160; The 1996 Plan authorizes the granting of
incentive and non-qualified stock options, restricted stock and performance
awards (collectively, &#147;1996 Plan Awards&#148;).&#160;
In addition, the 1996 Plan provides for the granting of options to
purchase common shares of AirNet Systems, Inc. at up to a 15% discount through
payroll deductions by employees of AirNet and its subsidiaries (the &#147;1996 Stock
Purchase Program&#148;).&#160; The 1996 Plan also
provides for the grant of non-qualified stock options to non-employee
directors.&#160; The maximum number of common
shares available for issuance under the 1996 Plan is 1,650,000.&#160; The 1996 Plan is administered by the
Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors, which determines the terms
and conditions applicable to the 1996 Plan Awards, other than options automatically
granted to non-employee directors in accordance with the terms of the 1996
Plan.&#160; The exercise price of each option
has been equal to the</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">42</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">fair market price of a common share on the date of grant.&#160; An option&#146;s maximum term is ten years (five
years for ISOs granted to 10% shareholders).&#160;
Option vesting periods range from vesting upon grant to vesting over
four years.&#160; Subsequent to the adoption
of the 2004 Plan, no additional 1996 Plan Awards will be made under the 1996
Plan.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A summary of AirNet&#146;s option activity and related information follows
(in thousands, except remaining contractual life and price per share data) for
the years ended December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s stock purchase program, which is part of the 1996 Plan and the
2004 Plan, allows eligible employees the opportunity to acquire common shares
of AirNet at up to a 15% discount through payroll deductions.&#160; AirNet issued 35,914, 39,597, and 26,552
common shares respectively during 2004, 2003, and 2002 from treasury shares
under the stock purchase program.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">6.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Lease
Obligations</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet leases facility space and courier vehicles at various locations
throughout the United States.&#160; In
addition, in 2002, AirNet entered into operating leases for four Cessna Caravan
208 aircraft each with a lease term of three years and two Cessna Caravan 208B
aircraft, one with a lease term of 3.5 years and one with a lease term of 4.5
years.&#160; The three-year lease terms were
subsequently extended an additional year.&#160;
AirNet incurred lease expense of $3,439,000, $4,131,000, and $3,747,000
for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, 2003 and 2002, respectively.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2004, future minimum
lease payments by year and in the aggregate under non-cancelable operating
leases with initial or remaining terms exceeding one year are as follows:&#160; 2005 - $912,000; 2006 - $384,000; 2007 -
$104,000; 2008 - $78,000; 2009 - $78,000.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Concurrently
with the sale of AirNet&#146;s Port Columbus Facility in December&nbsp;2004, AirNet
entered into the New Port Columbus Lease.&#160;
Pursuant to the New Port Columbus Lease, AirNet will lease the real
property associated with the Port Columbus Facility and the buildings and all
other improvements thereon pending completion of the construction of AirNet&#146;s
new office and hangar facility at Rickenbacker.&#160;
The term of the New Port Columbus Lease commenced on December&nbsp;15,
2004 and</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">43</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='43',FILE='C:\JMS\Snagara\05-2037-1\task379752\2037-1-ba-02.htm',USER='kkthiyagarajan',CD='Mar 31 21:12 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">will
terminate on the earlier to occur of (i) the date AirNet moves into the
Rickenbacker Facility or (ii) August&nbsp;31, 2005.&nbsp; The New Port Columbus
Lease will be rent free until May 15, 2005 and commencing May 16, 2005, the
rent will be $30,000 per month.&nbsp; The New Port Columbus Lease is a net
lease under which AirNet is responsible for all costs of operating the Port
Columbus Facility.&#160; This transaction is a
minor sale-leaseback, as the present value of the rental payments is less than
10% of the property&#146;s fair value; therefore, AirNet recorded a gain on the sale
of $0.3 million in 2004.&#160; AirNet intends
to move its operations at the Port Columbus Facility as well as its
administrative functions to the Rickenbacker Facility during the second quarter
of 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">7.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Related
Party Transactions</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2001, the Board of Directors approved a retirement agreement
with Gerald G. Mercer, Founder and former Chairman, of AirNet Systems,
Inc.&#160; As contemplated by the retirement
agreement, Mr. Mercer retired as Chairman and a Director effective August&nbsp;3,
2001.&#160; Under the terms of the retirement
agreement, Mr. Mercer had the option to sell up to $250,000 of AirNet Systems,
Inc. common shares each quarter of 2002 to AirNet based on then current market
prices.&#160; Mr. Mercer exercised his option
and, effective January&nbsp;2, 2003, sold 52,410 AirNet Systems, Inc. common
shares to AirNet at a total cost of $249,996.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Also under the terms of his retirement agreement, Mr. Mercer retained
his rights to sell his remaining AirNet common shares to private investors at
any time in accordance with the applicable laws.&#160; On or about December&nbsp;26, 2002, Mr.
Mercer sold an aggregate of 733,200 common shares to seven separate investors
in privately negotiated transactions.&#160; On
December&nbsp;24, 2002, he made a gift of 256,800 common shares to Spring Hill
Camps, which sold those common shares to three separate investors, one of which
also purchased common shares from Mr. Mercer, in privately negotiated
transactions.&#160; In connection with and as
a condition to the investors&#146; consummating those transactions, AirNet granted
registration rights with respect to the 990,000 common shares collectively
purchased by these investors from Mr. Mercer or Spring Hill Camps and
registered the common shares in 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">8.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Retirement
Plan</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet has a 401(k) retirement savings plan.&#160; All associates who have completed a minimum
of one month of service may contribute up to 60% of their eligible annual
earnings to the 401(k) retirement savings plan.&#160;
AirNet may elect, at its discretion, to make matching and profit-sharing
contributions.&#160; AirNet&#146;s contribution
expense related to the 401(k) retirement savings plan totaled $626</font>,000, $519,000, and $481,000 for the
years ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, 2003, and 2002, respectively.</p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">9.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Income
Taxes</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In
connection with the 1996 repurchase and cancellation of the Donald Wright
Warrant, AirNet recognized a related tax benefit estimated to be $7.0 million
based upon management&#146;s judgment and estimation of the portion of the Donald
Wright Warrant which would be deductible for income tax purposes.&#160; This tax benefit was recognized as additional
paid-in capital on AirNet&#146;s consolidated balance sheet and has had no effect on
AirNet&#146;s consolidated statement of operations.&#160;
During the third quarter 2003, this matter was partially resolved and
AirNet has realized tax deductions related to this transaction in excess of
management&#146;s original estimates resulting in additional tax benefits.&#160; The additional tax benefits associated with
the deductible portion of the Donald Wright Warrant have exceeded the original
estimate by $1.3 million.&#160; The additional
tax benefits, as was the initial estimated tax benefit associated with the
Donald Wright Warrant, have been recorded as an increase to additional paid-in
capital.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">10.&#160; Discontinued Operations</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On August&nbsp;11, 2003, AirNet Systems, Inc.
completed the sale of substantially all of the assets of its Mercury Business
Services unit to Mercury Business Services, Inc., a Delaware corporation owned
by a group that includes the original owners of the Mercury business.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet sold the assets, primarily the accounts receivable, personal
property and intellectual property, with a carrying amount at the time of sale
of approximately $1.0 million, for approximately $1.1 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet received approximately $455,000 of the
purchase price in a ninety day promissory note secured by the assets being sold
and guaranteed by each of the shareholders of Mercury Business Services, Inc.
Under terms of the Asset Purchase Agreement, approximately $536,000 of the
purchase price was paid with AirNet Systems, Inc. common shares owned by the
shareholders of Mercury Business Services, Inc., including 56,000 common shares
tendered to AirNet Systems, Inc.,</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">45</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
