<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">prior to the closing at $4.30 per common share
(the closing price of the AirNet Systems, Inc., common shares on NYSE on July&nbsp;25,
2003) and 68,494 common shares tendered to AirNet Systems, Inc., on the closing
date at $4.31 per common share (the average closing price of the AirNet
Systems, Inc., common shares on NYSE on August&nbsp;4-6, 2003). The balance of
the purchase price was paid in cash.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
has reported these operations as discontinued operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Mercury Business Services unit had revenues for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
2003, which consisted of the seven months prior to the sale, of $5.9 million as
compared to $8.9 million for the full year in 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Pre-tax
loss for AirNet&#146;s Mercury Business Services unit for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
2003, which consisted of the seven months prior to the sale, was $13,000, as
compared to a $432,000 pre-tax loss for the full year 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">11.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Net
Income (Loss) Per Share</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table sets forth the computation of basic and diluted net
income (loss) per share for the years ended December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">.15</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For the years
ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, 2003, and 2002, options covering 686,000,
981,000, and 697,000 common shares, respectively, were excluded from the
diluted weighted average shares outstanding calculation, as their exercise
prices exceeded the average fair market value of the underlying common shares
for the year.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">12.</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Litigation
and Contingencies</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet is subject
to claims and lawsuits in the ordinary course of its business.&#160; In the opinion of management, the outcomes of
these actions, which are not clearly determinable at the present time, are
either adequately covered by insurance, or if not insured, will not, in the
aggregate, have a material adverse impact upon AirNet&#146;s financial position or
the results of future operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

incorporated herein by reference from the table captioned &#147;Selected Quarterly
Data (Unaudited)&#148; in &#147;Item 7- Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial
Condition and Results of Operation&#148; of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-1.0in;"><a name="Item9__124028"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 9.</font></b></a><b><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;"> </font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">CHANGES IN AND DISAGREEMENTS WITH
ACCOUNTANTS ON ACCOUNTING AND FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-1.0in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:45.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">No response required.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:45.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item9a__124031"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 9A.</font></b></a><b><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;"> </font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">CONTROLS
AND PROCEDURES.</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Evaluation of Disclosure Controls and Procedures</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">With the participation of the Chairman of the Board, Chief Executive Officer and President (the principal executive officer) and the Chief Financial Officer, Treasurer and Secretary&#160; (the principal financial officer) of AirNet Systems, Inc. (&#147;AirNet&#148;), AirNet&#146;s management has evaluated the effectiveness of AirNet&#146;s disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Rule&nbsp;13a-15(e) under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#147;Exchange Act&#148;)), as of the end of the fiscal year covered by this Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K.&#160; Based on that evaluation, AirNet&#146;s Chairman of the Board, Chief Executive Officer and President and AirNet&#146;s Chief Financial Officer, Treasurer and Secretary have concluded that:</font></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p><p style="font-size:10
.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 62.65pt;text-indent:-23.75pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font face="Times New Roman">information required to be disclosed by AirNet in this Annual Report on Form 10-K and the other reports that AirNet files or submits under the Exchange Act would be accumulated and communicated to AirNet&#146;s management, including its principal executive officer and principal financial officer, as appropriate to allow timely decisions regarding required disclosure;</font></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 62.65pt;text-indent:-23.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p><p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 62.65pt;text-indent:-23.75pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New 
Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font face="Times New Roman">information required to be disclosed by AirNet in this Annual Report on Form 10-K and the other reports that AirNet files or submits under the Exchange Act would be recorded, processed, summarized and reported within the time periods specified in the SEC&#146;s rules and forms; and</font></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 62.65pt;text-indent:-23.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p><p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 62.65pt;text-indent:-23.75pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#
160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font face="Times New Roman">AirNet&#146;s disclosure controls and procedures are effective as of the end of the fiscal year covered by this Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K to ensure that material information relating to AirNet and its consolidated subsidiaries is made known to them, particularly during the period for which the periodic reports of AirNet, including this Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K, are being prepared.</font></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 62.65pt;text-indent:-23.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Changes in Internal Control over Financial Reporting</font></b></p><p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">There
were no changes in AirNet&#146;s internal control over financial reporting (as
defined in Rule 13a-15(f) under the Exchange Act) that occurred during AirNet&#146;s
fiscal quarter ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, that have materially affected, or
are reasonably likely to materially affect, AirNet&#146;s internal control over
financial reporting.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item9b__124037"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 9B.</font></b></a><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">OTHER INFORMATION</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Changes in Compensation of Directors</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Directors
of AirNet who are not officers or employees of AirNet (&#147;Non-Employee Directors&#148;)
are paid fees for their services as members of the Board of Directors and as
members of Board committees.&#160; The
quarterly fee paid in 2004 and to be paid in 2005 for serving as a Non-Employee
Director was and remains $6,000.&#160; The fee
for attending each meeting of the full Board of Directors in person was $2,000
in 2004 and continues to be the same amount in 2005.&#160; The fee for attending telephonic meetings of
the full Board was $2,000 in 2004.&#160; At a
meeting held on December&nbsp;22, 2004, the Non-Employee Directors discussed,
and on March&nbsp;9, 2005, the Board of Directors affirmed that, effective for
the telephonic meetings of the full Board held after January&nbsp;1, 2005, the
fee would be $1,000 for each meeting attended.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
fee for Audit Committee members was $2,000 per meeting attended in 2004, with
the Chair of the Audit Committee receiving an additional $1,000 per meeting
attended.&#160; The fee for Compensation
Committee members and Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee members was
$1,000 per meeting attended in 2004, with the Chair of each of those Committees
receiving an additional $2,000 for each meeting of the Committee attended.&#160; At a meeting held on December&nbsp;22, 2004,
the Non-Employee Directors discussed, and on March&nbsp;9, 2005, the Board of
Directors affirmed that</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">47</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">the
fees for attending in person Committee meetings held after January&nbsp;1, 2005
would remain the same as they had been in 2004; however, the fees for attending
telephonic meetings of each Committee held after January&nbsp;1, 2005 would be
one-half (50%) of the amount of the fees for attending a meeting of the
particular Committee in person.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As
the lead director of AirNet, James&nbsp;E. Riddle received an additional
quarterly fee of $6,000 for service in that capacity in 2004 and continues to
receive that quarterly fee in 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Non-Employee Directors meet without management present in connection with each
of the regularly scheduled meetings of the full Board and receive no meeting
fees for attending such meetings.&#160; To the
extent the Non-Employee Directors determine to meet by telephone or in person
other than in connection with a regularly scheduled Board meeting, they will
receive $2,000 per meeting attended in person or $1,000 per telephone
meeting.&#160; AirNet&#146;s Non-Employee Directors
are reimbursed for out-of-pocket expenses incurred in connection with their
service as directors, including travel expenses.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As
an officer and employee of AirNet, Joel&nbsp;E. Biggerstaff receives no
additional compensation for serving as a director of AirNet.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under
the terms of the AirNet Systems, Inc. 2004 Stock Incentive Plan (the &#147;2004 Plan&#148;),
which was approved by the shareholders of AirNet on June&nbsp;4, 2004, on the
first business day of each fiscal year of AirNet, each individual who is then
serving as a Non-Employee Director and has served for at least one full
one-year term as a Non-Employee director, is to be automatically granted an
option to purchase 4,000 AirNet common shares with an exercise price equal to
the fair market value of the underlying common shares on the grant date.&#160; However, each of the individuals serving as a
Non-Employee Director of AirNet on January&nbsp;3, 2005 (the first business day
of the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2005) &#151; Russell M. Gertmenian,
David P. Lauer, Bruce D. Parker and James E. Riddle &#151; determined not to accept
the option to purchase 4,000 AirNet common shares which would have been
automatically granted to him on that date.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Changes in Compensation of Executive Officers</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:37.05pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December&nbsp;16, 2004, the Compensation Committee
determined to increase the annual base salary of Gary&nbsp;W. Qualmann, the
Chief Financial Officer, Treasurer and Secretary of AirNet, from $190,000 to
$215,000.&#160; This increase was effective January&nbsp;1,
2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:37.05pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:37.05pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December&nbsp;16, 2004, the Compensation Committee
determined to modify the annual base salary and other compensation arrangements
of Robert&nbsp;L. Austin, the Senior Vice President, Jetride Services of
AirNet.&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Austin&#146;s annual base
salary was increased from $185,000 to $200,000.&#160;
These modifications were effective January&nbsp;1, 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:37.05pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Adoption of 2005 Incentive Compensation Plan</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On February 2, 2005, the
Board of Directors of AirNet, upon the recommendation of the Compensation
Committee, adopted the 2005 Incentive Compensation Plan (the &#147;Incentive
Plan&#148;).&#160; The Compensation Committee and
the Board of Directors subsequently approved clarifications and modifications
to the Incentive Plan on March 8, 2005 and March 29, 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The purpose of the Incentive
Plan is to promote the following goals of AirNet for the fiscal year ending on
December 31, 2005 (&#147;Fiscal 2005&#148;) by providing incentive compensation to
certain employees of AirNet and its subsidiaries:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#149;</font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>Exceeding budgeted pre-tax income;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#149;</font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>Reducing fixed costs;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#149;</font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>Creating and executing contingency plans for changes in AirNet&#146;s Bank
business;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#149;</font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>Refining AirNet&#146;s business plan for its Express and Jetride businesses
to more quickly and profitably diversify AirNet;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#149;</font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>Developing AirNet&#146;s leadership team; and</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#149;</font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>Meeting high priority deadlines related to compliance with the
Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 and other key projects.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Participants in the Incentive
Plan include AirNet's executive officers, including Joel E. Biggerstaff
(Chairman of the Board, Chief Executive Officer and President), Gary W.
Qualmann (Chief Financial Officer, Treasurer and Secretary), Larry M.
Glasscock, Jr. (Senior Vice President, Express Services), Jeffery B. Harris
(Senior Vice President, Bank Services), Robert L. Austin (Senior Vice
President, Jetride Services), Craig A. Leach (Vice President, Information
Systems) and Wynn D. Peterson (Vice President, Strategic Planning and Analysis)
and certain department managers and department directors.&#160; At the start of Fiscal 2005, there were 45
participants in the Incentive Plan.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Payments under the Incentive
Plan are based on a combination of AirNet&#146;s pre-tax income for Fiscal 2005,
operating performance of AirNet&#146;s various business components, and the
achievement of personal goals assigned to each participant. The Compensation
Committee approves personal goals for each of the executive officers and
reviews the personal goals established by senior management for other
participants. The personal goals approved by the Compensation Committee for
each of the executive officers relate to specific business objectives related
to general business operations (e.g., regulatory compliance, expense
reductions, etc.) and each business component (e.g., execution of specific
contracts with customers and vendors, cost reductions, service improvements,
etc.).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">No incentive compensation
will be paid under the Incentive Plan unless AirNet achieves a designated
threshold level of pre-tax income for Fiscal 2005.&#160; Once the designated threshold level is achieved,
incentive compensation payments will increase at predetermined pre-tax income
levels until the maximum compensation payout of $1.9 million is reached at
approximately 200% of Fiscal 2004 pre-tax income, determined without regard to
the Fiscal 2004 impairment charges related to property and equipment and
goodwill.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Once the overall amount of
incentive compensation is determined based upon AirNet&#146;s pre-tax income,
incentive compensation will be allocated to Bank, Express, Jetride and
corporate based upon pre-established targets.&#160;
Incentive compensation will then be allocated to the participants most
closely involved in managing each of those business areas based upon each
participant&#146;s base salary.&#160; Finally,
participants must achieve their pre-established personal goals to achieve their
maximum incentive compensation payment.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The maximum percentage of
annual base salary that each of the executive officers may receive as incentive
compensation under the Incentive Plan is as follows: Joel E. Biggerstaff, 100%;
Gary W. Qualmann, Larry M. Glasscock, Jr., Jeffrey B. Harris, and Robert L.
Austin, 75%; and Craig A. Leach and Wynn D. Peterson, 50%.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Except for payments to executive
officers, payments under the Incentive Plan will be paid in quarterly payments
commencing with the second quarter of Fiscal 2005 based upon AirNet&#146;s year to
date financial performance.&#160; Payments of
incentive compensation to the executive officers will be made in the first
quarter of Fiscal 2006 based upon AirNet&#146;s performance for Fiscal 2005.&#160; In order to receive payment, a participant
must be actively employed by AirNet or one of its subsidiaries at the time payment
is made.&#160; New employees who qualify for
the Incentive Plan will be eligible to participate on the first day of the
calendar quarter following their date of hire.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Compensation Committee
may amend, modify or terminate the Incentive Plan at any time.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">48</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Modification of Financing Arrangements</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On March 24, 2005, AirNet and its lenders entered into a &#147;Second Change
in Terms Agreement&#148; that further modified the terms and conditions of the
Amended Credit Agreement.&#160; In accordance
with the Second Change in Terms Agreement, AirNet prepaid in full the remaining
$11.0 balance outstanding on its secured term loan.&#160;&#160; Upon the prepayment of the term loan, the
term loan portion of the Amended Credit Agreement was terminated.&#160; In addition, the revolving credit facility
under the Amended Credit Agreement was reduced from $35.0 million to $30.0
million.&#160; In the event AirNet secures
permanent financing on all or a portion of its Rickenbacker Facility, the
revolving credit facility will be reduced from $30.0 million to $25.0 million.&#160; Under the Second Change in Terms Agreement,
the term of the revolving credit facility was extended from September 30, 2005
to October 15, 2006. The December 31, 2004 Balance Sheet gives effect to the
Second Change in Terms Agreement entered into on March 24, 2005.&#160; The Second Change in Terms Agreement also
provided for the release of certain fixed assets that were securing the loans
under the Amended Credit Facility and modified certain other financial
covenants.&#160; On March 24, 2005, in
connection with Second Change in Terms Agreement, The Huntington National Bank
and JPMorgan Chase Bank, N.A., successor by merger to Bank One, N.A., purchased
the interest of Fifth Third Bank in the secured revolving credit facility
portion of the Amended Credit Agreement (respectively, the &#147;HNB Assignment
Agreement&#148; and &#147;Chase Assignment Agreement&#148;).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Second Change in Terms Agreement, the HNB
Assignment Agreement and the Chase Assignment Agreement are filed in this
Annual Report on Form 10-K as Exhibit 4.39, Exhibit 4.40, and Exhibit 4.41,
respectively, and the descriptions herein are qualified in their entirety by
reference to the full terms and conditions thereof, which terms and conditions
are incorporated herein by reference in their entirety.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">On March 24, 2005, AirNet entered into a three-year term loan totaling
$11.0 million with a fixed interest rate of 8.12%.&#160; This term loan is secured by seven Cessna
Caravans and nine LearJet 35&#146;s from AirNet&#146;s cargo aircraft fleet with a
combined net book value as of December 31, 2004 of approximately $19.9
million.&#160; The aircraft securing this loan
were released from the collateral securing the loans under Amended Credit
Agreement in accordance with the Second Change in Terms Agreement.&#160; The proceeds from this term loan were used to
prepay in full AirNet&#146;s term loan under the Amended Credit Facility as
described above.&#160; The December 31, 2004
Balance Sheet reflects the reclassification of approximately $22.4 million from
current to long-term notes payable as a result of the extension of the Amended
Credit Facility under the Second Change in Terms Agreement and the financing of
the cargo aircraft described above.&#160; The
Loan and Security Agreement and related Business Purpose Promissary Note dated
March 24, 2005 is filed in this Annual Report on Form 10-K as Exhibit 4.44 and
4.45, respectively and the description herein is qualified in its entirety by
reference to the full terms and conditions thereof</font>, which terms and
conditions are incorporated herein by reference in their entirety.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Engagement of Brown Gibbons Lang &amp; Company</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On January 5, 2005, upon the approval of the Board of Directors of
AirNet, AirNet engaged Brown Gibbons Lang &amp; Company (&#147;BGL&#148;) to serve as
AirNet's exclusive financial advisor and investment banker to review, develop
and evaluate various strategic alternatives to enhance shareholder value.&#160; BGL's analysis will address, among other
things, capitalization, growth and value realization transaction alternatives
that may be available to AirNet.&#160; Such alternatives
may include one or more of the following: potential acquisitions or
divestitures, a sale of AirNet or one or more of its business units, the
raising of additional capital or the refinancing or restructuring of the
AirNet's existing capital structure.&#160; BGL
has not been engaged to analyze, or advise AirNet with respect to, any
particular transaction.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2005 Annual Meeting of
Shareholders</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">To date, AirNet has not set a
date for its 2005 Annual Meeting of Shareholders.&#160; Accordingly, the information required by Part
III (Items 10, 11, 12, 13 and 14) of Form 10-K has been provided as part of this
Annual Report on Form 10-K.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='50',FILE='C:\JMS\Snagara\05-2037-1\task379752\2037-1-ba-02.htm',USER='kkthiyagarajan',CD='Mar 31 21:12 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">There
are no family relationships among any of the directors and executive officers
of AirNet.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Director Independence</font></b></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Board of Directors of AirNet (the &#147;Board&#148;) has
established categorical standards to assist it in making its determination of
director independence.&#160; The Board defines
an &#147;independent director&#148; to be a director who:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>is not and has not been within the last three
years an employee of, and whose immediate family members are not and have not
been within the last three years an executive officer of, AirNet or any of
AirNet&#146;s subsidiaries;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>has not received, and whose immediate family
members have not received other than for service as a non-executive officer
employee, during any 12-month period within the last three years, more than
$100,000 in direct compensation from AirNet or any of AirNet&#146;s subsidiaries,
other than director and committee fees and pension or other forms of deferred
compensation for prior service (provided such compensation is not contingent in
any way on continued service);</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>is not and whose immediate family members are
not a current partner of a firm that is AirNet&#146;s internal or external auditor;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>is not a current employee of a firm that is
AirNet&#146;s internal or external auditor;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>whose immediate family members are not a
current employee of a firm that is AirNet&#146;s internal or external auditor and participates
in the firm&#146;s audit, assurance or tax compliance (but not tax planning)
practice;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>has not been, and whose immediate family
members have not been, within the last three years (but is no longer) a partner
or employee of a firm that is AirNet&#146;s internal or external auditor and
personally worked on AirNet&#146;s audit within that time;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>is not and has not been within the last three
years employed, and whose immediate family members are not and have not been
within the last three years employed, as an executive officer of another
company where any of AirNet&#146;s present executive officers at the same time
serves or served on that other company&#146;s compensation committee;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>is not a current employee, and whose immediate
family members are not a current executive officer, of a company that has made
payments to, or received payments from, AirNet or any of AirNet&#146;s subsidiaries
for property or services in an amount which, in any of the last three fiscal
years, exceeds the greater of $1 million, or 2% of such other company&#146;s
consolidated gross revenues; and</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>has no other material relationship with AirNet
or any of AirNet&#146;s subsidiaries (either directly or as a partner, shareholder
or officer of an organization that has a relationship with AirNet or any of
AirNet&#146;s subsidiaries).</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 71.25pt;text-indent:-36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Board has determined that
each of David P. Lauer, Bruce D. Parker and James E. Riddle is independent
under these categorical standards and has no relationship with AirNet (either
directly or indirectly), other than serving as a director of AirNet and holding
common shares of AirNet.&#160; Joel E.
Biggerstaff and Russell M. Gertmenian do not qualify as independent directors
under the foregoing categorical standards.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">51</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Executive Officers of AirNet</font></b></p>

of AirNet as of March&nbsp;28, 2005.&#160; The
executive officers serve at the pleasure of the Board and in the case of Joel
E. Biggerstaff and Jeffery B. Harris pursuant to employment agreements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Joel&nbsp;E. Biggerstaff</font></i></b> has served as AirNet&#146;s Chairman of the Board
since August&nbsp;2001, Chief Executive Officer since April&nbsp;2000, and
President since August&nbsp;1999.&#160; He
also served as AirNet&#146;s Chief Operating Officer from August&nbsp;1999 to February&nbsp;2004.&#160; He has also served as a director of AirNet
since May 2000.&#160; Prior to joining AirNet,
Mr.&nbsp;Biggerstaff served as President of the Southern Region of Corporate
Express Delivery Systems, a national expedited distribution service, from February&nbsp;1998
through July&nbsp;1999.&#160; From September&nbsp;1996
through February&nbsp;1998, Mr.&nbsp;Biggerstaff provided transportation
consulting services and prior to September&nbsp;1996, he held various
positions, including Regional Vice President and General Manager, with Ryder
Systems, Inc., a company providing transportation and supply-chain management
solutions.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Gary&nbsp;W. Qualmann</font></i></b> has served AirNet as the Chief Financial
Officer, Treasurer and Secretary since September&nbsp;2, 2003.&#160; Prior to joining AirNet, from February&nbsp;2002
through August&nbsp;2003, Mr.&nbsp;Qualmann served as Chief Financial Officer
and Treasurer of Metatec, Inc., a manufacturer and distributor of electronic
media which filed a voluntary petition for reorganization under Chapter&nbsp;11
of the United States Bankruptcy Code on October&nbsp;17, 2003.&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Qualmann provided financial
consulting services to Metatec from October&nbsp;2001 through February&nbsp;2002.&#160; From March&nbsp;1996 until June&nbsp;2001,
Mr.&nbsp;Qualmann was Chief Financial Officer, Treasurer and Secretary of
MindLeaders.com, Inc., an e-learning company based in Columbus, Ohio.&#160; From May 1988 until July&nbsp;1995,
Mr.&nbsp;Qualmann served as Executive Vice President and Chief Financial
Officer of Red Roof Inns, Inc., a lodging company based in Hilliard, Ohio.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Larry&nbsp;M. Glasscock, Jr.</font></i></b> joined AirNet as Senior Vice President,
Express Services in February&nbsp;2003.&#160;
From February&nbsp;2002 through February&nbsp;2003, Mr.&nbsp;Glasscock
served as Senior Vice President of Evercom Systems, Inc., a national provider
of telecom services.&#160; From April&nbsp;2001
through February&nbsp;2002, Mr.&nbsp;Glasscock served as Executive Vice President
of NextJet Technologies, a software and technology solutions organization.&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Glasscock served as Chief Executive
Officer of Expedited Delivery Systems, Inc., a time-definite trucking concern,
from August&nbsp;1999 to September&nbsp;2000 and as its President and Chief
Operating Officer from January&nbsp;1998 through August&nbsp;1999.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Jeffery&nbsp;B. Harris</font></i></b> has served AirNet as Senior Vice President,
Bank Services since May 2000.&#160;
Mr.&nbsp;Harris joined AirNet in June&nbsp;1996 as the relationship
manager for Banking Sales and was appointed Vice President, Sales in the
banking division in October&nbsp;1997.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Robert&nbsp;L. Austin</font></i></b> has served AirNet as Senior Vice President,
Jetride Services since February&nbsp;2005.&#160;
From 2003 to 2005, Mr.&nbsp;Austin served AirNet as Vice President of
Jetride Private Charter.&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Austin
joined AirNet in February&nbsp;1988 as the Aircraft Sales and Acquisition
Director and was appointed Manager of the Jetride Private Charter division in January&nbsp;2001.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Craig&nbsp;A. Leach</font></i></b> has served AirNet as Vice President,
Information Systems since January&nbsp;2000.&#160;
Mr.&nbsp;Leach established AirNet&#146;s Information Systems Department in
1985 and was named Director of Information Systems in 1996.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Wynn D. Peterson</font></i></b> has served AirNet as Vice President,
Strategic Planning and Analysis since January&nbsp;2005.&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Peterson has served as an officer of
AirNet since February&nbsp;2000 when he was named Vice President of Corporate
Development.&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Peterson joined
AirNet in 1997 as Manager of Corporate Development.&#160; Prior to joining AirNet, Mr.&nbsp;Peterson
managed equity and fixed income portfolios from 1993 until 1997 at Desert
Mutual, a pension and benefits company in Salt Lake City, Utah.&#160; From 1988 until 1993, Mr.&nbsp;Peterson held
various management positions in Finance, Corporate Development and Strategic
Planning at AMR Corporation, the parent company of American Airlines, Inc., in
Dallas, Texas.</p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">52</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Composition of Committees of Board of Directors</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Board has three standing committees&nbsp;&#151; the
Audit Committee, the Compensation Committee and the Nominating and Corporate
Governance Committee.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Audit Committee</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Audit Committee consists of David P. Lauer
(Chair), Bruce D. Parker and James E. Riddle.&#160;
The Board has determined that each member of the Audit Committee
qualifies as an independent director under the applicable sections of the New
York Stock Exchange Listed Company Manual (the &#147;NYSE Rules&#148;) and under
Rule&nbsp;10A-3 under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#147;Exchange
Act&#148;).&#160; The Board has also determined that
David P. Lauer qualifies as an &#147;audit committee financial expert&#148; for purposes
of Item&nbsp;401(h) of SEC Regulation&nbsp;S-K, by virtue of his experience
described above under &#147;<b><font style="font-weight:bold;">Directors of AirNet</font></b>.&#148;&#160; In addition to the qualification of Mr. Lauer
as an &#147;audit committee financial expert,&#148; the Board strongly believes that each
member of the Audit Committee is highly qualified to discharge his duties on
behalf of AirNet and its subsidiaries and satisfies the financial literacy
requirement of the applicable NYSE Rules.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">David P. Lauer currently serves on the audit
committee of five public companies, including AirNet.&#160; AirNet&#146;s Board has determined that such
simultaneous service will not impair Mr.&nbsp;Lauer&#146;s ability to effectively
serve on AirNet&#146;s Audit Committee.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Compensation
Committee</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Compensation Committee is comprised of James E.
Riddle (Chair), David P. Lauer and Bruce D. Parker.&#160; The Board has determined that each member of
the Compensation Committee qualifies as an independent director under the
applicable NYSE Rules, an outside director for purposes of Section&nbsp;162(m)
of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended (the &#147;Internal Revenue Code&#148;),
and a non-employee director for purposes of Rule 16b-3 under the Exchange Act.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Nominating and
Corporate Governance Committee</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee is
comprised of Bruce D. Parker (Chair), David P. Lauer and James E. Riddle.&#160; The Board has determined that each member of
the Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee qualifies as an independent
director under the applicable NYSE Rules.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Section&nbsp;16(a) Beneficial Ownership Reporting Compliance</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Ownership of and transactions in AirNet&#146;s common
shares by executive officers, directors and persons who beneficially own more
than 10% of the common shares are required to be reported to the SEC pursuant
to Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Exchange Act.&#160;
Based solely on a review of copies of the reports furnished to AirNet
and written representations that no other reports were required, AirNet
believes that during the 2004 fiscal year, all filing requirements were
complied with, except t</font>hat each of Robert L. Austin, Denise D. Brown, Joel E.
Biggerstaff, Larry M. Glasscock, Jr., Jeffery B. Harris, Craig A. Leach, Wynn
D. Peterson, Gary W. Qualmann and Michael Snyder, filed late one report,
covering one transaction &#151; the grant of an option.&#160; In addition, during the 2003 fiscal year, Mr.
Qualmann filed late one report, covering one transaction &#150; the grant of an
option.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Corporate Governance Documents</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s Board has adopted charters for each of the
Audit Committee, the Compensation Committee and the Nominating and Corporate
Governance Committee as well as Corporate Governance Guidelines as contemplated
by the applicable NYSE Rules.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In accordance with the requirements of Section&nbsp;303A.10
of the NYSE Rules, the AirNet Board has adopted a Code of Business Conduct and
Ethics covering the directors, officers and employees (team members) of AirNet,
including AirNet&#146;s Chairman of the Board, Chief Executive Officer and President
(the principal executive officer), AirNet&#146;s Chief Financial Officer, Treasurer
and Secretary (the principal financial officer) and AirNet&#146;s Controller and
Principal Accounting Officer. AirNet intends to disclose the following under
the &#147;Corporate Governance&#148; link on the &#147;Investor Relations&#148; page of its website
located at www.airnet.com within four business days following their occurrence
as required by the applicable rules of the SEC and the requirements of Section&nbsp;303A.10
of the NYSE Rules:&#160; (A)&nbsp;the date and
nature of any amendment to a provision of its Code of Business Conduct and
Ethics that (i) applies to AirNet&#146;s principal executive officer, principal
financial officer, principal accounting officer or controller, or persons
performing similar functions, (ii) relates to any element of the &#147;code of
ethics&#148; definition enumerated in Item 406(b) of SEC Regulation S-K, and (iii)
is not a technical, administrative or other non-substantive amendment; and (B)
a description of any waiver (including the nature of the waiver, the name of
the person to whom the waiver was granted and the date of the waiver),
including an implicit waiver, from a provision of the</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">53</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Code
of Business Conduct and Ethics granted to AirNet&#146;s principal executive officer,
principal financial officer, principal accounting officer or controller, or
persons performing similar functions, that relates to one or more of the items
set forth in Item 406(b) of SEC Regulation S-K.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The text of each of the Audit Committee Charter, the
Compensation Committee Charter, the Nominating and Corporate Governance
Committee Charter, the Corporate Governance Guidelines and the Code of Business
Conduct and Ethics is posted under the &#147;Corporate Governance&#148; link on the &#147;Investor
Relations&#148; page of AirNet&#146;s website located at www.airnet.com . Interested
persons may also obtain copies of the Audit Committee Charter, the Compensation
Committee Charter, the Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee Charter,
the Corporate Governance Guidelines and the Code of Business Conduct and
Ethics, without charge, by writing to the Chief Financial Officer, Treasurer
and Secretary of AirNet at AirNet Systems, Inc., 3939 International Gateway,
Columbus, Ohio 43219, Attention: Gary W. Qualmann.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Communications with the Board</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:37.05pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In accordance with AirNet&#146;s Corporate Governance
Guidelines and applicable NYSE Rules, the non-management directors of AirNet
meet (without management present) at regularly scheduled executive sessions at
least twice per year and at such other times as the directors deem necessary or
appropriate.&#160; James E. Riddle has been
chosen as the lead director and presides at all executive sessions of the
non-management directors of AirNet.&#160; In
addition, at least once a year, the independent directors of AirNet meet in
executive session.&#160; Mr. Riddle also
presides at those meetings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:37.05pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:37.05pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Board believes it is important for shareholders
to have a process to send communications to the Board and its individual
members.&#160; Accordingly, shareholders who
wish to communicate with the Board or a particular director may do so by
sending a letter to such individual or individuals, in care of AirNet, to
AirNet&#146;s executive offices at 3939 International Gateway, Columbus, Ohio
43219.&#160; The mailing envelope must contain
a clear notation indicating that the enclosed letter is a &#147;Shareholder &#150; Board
Communication&#148; or &#147;Shareholder &#150; Director Communication,&#148; as appropriate.&#160; All such letters must identify the author as
a shareholder and clearly state whether the intended recipients are all members
of the Board or certain specified individual directors.&#160; Copies of all such letters will be circulated
to the appropriate director or directors.&#160;
In addition, shareholders may contact the directors through the
Mysafeworkplace.com Hotline.&#160; The
Mysafeworkplace.com Hotline can be reached at 800-461-9330 or via e-mail at
www.mysafeworkplace.com.&#160; All shareholder
communications through the Mysafeworkplace.com Hotline will be forwarded to the
appropriate director or directors.&#160; There
is no screening process in respect of shareholder communications.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:37.05pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item11_124055"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 11 </font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">&#150; EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Executive Compensation Tables</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following information is provided with respect to
AirNet&#146;s Chief Executive Officer and each of AirNet&#146;s four other most highly
compensated executive officers serving as an executive officer at December&nbsp;31,
2004.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>

<p align="left" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">(1)</font></i></b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font style="font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">&#147;All
Other Compensation&#148; for the 2004 fiscal year includes:&#160; (a) employer matching contributions in the
amounts of&#160; $3,990, $2,550, $3,954,
$4,895, and $6,500 allocated to their accounts under the AirNet Systems, Inc.
Retirement Savings Plan on behalf of Messrs. Biggerstaff, Harris, Qualmann,
Wright and Glasscock, respectively; (b) reimbursements in the amounts of
$2,368, $1,647, $2,200, $4,179, and $0 related to life insurance premium
payments made by Messrs. Biggerstaff, Harris, Qualmann, Wright and Glasscock,
respectively; and (c) for Mr. Wright, the amount of $245,000 which has been
accrued and is to be paid in accordance with the terms of Mr. Wright&#146;s
employment separation agreement (discussed below under &#147;Employment Contracts
and Termination of Employment and Change-in-Control Arrangements&#148;) as a result
of the termination of his employment with AirNet.&#160; The AirNet Systems, Inc. Retirement Savings
Plan is a qualified, broad-based defined contribution plan under which amounts
are paid out the named individuals only upon retirement, termination of
employment, disability or death.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">(2)</font></i></b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font style="font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">Mr.
Qualmann became an executive officer of AirNet on September&nbsp;2, 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">(3)</font></i></b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font style="font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">Mr.
Wright ceased to be an executive officer and employee of AirNet effective December&nbsp;31,
2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">(4)</font></i></b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font style="font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">Mr.
Glasscock became an executive officer of AirNet on February&nbsp;17, 2004.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 27.35pt;text-align:left;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-27.35pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">&nbsp;</font></i></b></p>

<p align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Grants
of Options</font></i></b></p>

<p align="left" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;">&nbsp;</font></i></b></p>

summarizes information concerning options granted to the named individuals
during the 2004 fiscal year.&#160; AirNet has
never granted stock appreciation rights.</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 27.35pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-27.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Each option was granted on February&nbsp;17,
2004 under the AirNet Systems, Inc. Amended and Restated 1996 Incentive Stock
Plan (the &#147;1996 Plan&#148;).&#160; Each option
vested as to 20% of the common shares on each of the grant date and the first
anniversary of the grant date and will vest as to 20% of the common shares on
each of the second, third and fourth anniversaries of the grant date.&#160; At the discretion of the Compensation
Committee, the options may have stock-for-stock exercise and tax withholding
features.&#160; If AirNet merges with another
entity and AirNet is not the survivor in the merger, or if all or substantially
all of AirNet&#146;s assets or stock is acquired by another entity, each option
which has not expired, been cancelled or been exercised prior to the effective
date of such event, will immediately vest and become exercisable in full.&#160; If the employment of the option holder is
terminated by reason of death or total disability, the vested portion of the
option may be exercised for a period of 12 months, subject to its stated
term.&#160; If the employment of the option
holder is terminated for any other reason, the vested portion of the option may
be exercised for a period of three months, subject to its stated term.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 27.35pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-27.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 27.0pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>The dollar amounts reflected in this table are
the result of calculations at the 5% and 10% annual appreciation rates set by
the SEC for illustrative purposes, and assume the options are held until their
respective expiration dates.&#160; These
dollar amounts are not intended to forecast future performance or possible future
appreciation in the price of AirNet&#146;s common shares.&#160; Shareholders are, therefore, cautioned
against drawing any conclusions from the appreciation data shown, aside from
the fact that the option holders will only realize value from the option grants
shown if the price of AirNet&#146;s common shares appreciates, which benefits all
shareholders commensurately.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 27.0pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Option Exercises and Holdings</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

following table summarizes information concerning unexercised options held as
of December&nbsp;31, 2004 by each of the named individuals.&#160; None of these individuals exercised options
during the 2004 fiscal year.</font></p>
